macq.extract

Extract

Usage

See a specific technique below.

Debugging

Include the argument debug=True to Extract to enable debugging for any extraction technique.

_Note: debugging output and interfaces are unique to each method._

Extraction Techniques

  • Observer
  • SLAF
  • ARMS

Observer

Usage

from macq import generate, extract
from macq.observation import IdentityObservation

traces = generate.pddl.VanillaSampling(problem_id=123, plan_len=20, num_traces=100).traces
observations = traces.tokenize(IdentityObservation)
model = extract.Extract(observations, extract.modes.OBSERVER)

print(model.details())

Output:

  Fluents: at stone stone-03 location pos-04-06, at stone stone-01 location pos-04-06, at stone stone-02 location pos-05-06, at stone stone-06 location pos-07-04, at stone stone-11 ...
  Actions:
    push-to-goal stone stone-04 location pos-04-05 location pos-04-06 direction dir-up location pos-04-04 player player-01:
      precond:
        at player player-01 location pos-04-06
        at stone stone-04 location pos-04-05
        clear location pos-05-06
        ...
      add:
        at stone stone-04 location pos-04-04
        clear location pos-04-06
        at-goal stone stone-04
        at player player-01 location pos-04-05
      delete:
        at stone stone-04 location pos-04-05
        clear location pos-04-04
        at player player-01 location pos-04-06

observations = traces.tokenize(AtomicPartialObservation, percent_missing=0.10)

ARMS

Usage

from macq import generate, extract
from macq.trace import PlanningObject, Fluent, TraceList
from macq.observation import PartialObservation

def get_fluent(name: str, objs: list[str]):
    objects = [PlanningObject(o.split()[0], o.split()[1]) for o in objs]
    return Fluent(name, objects)

traces = TraceList()
generator = generate.pddl.TraceFromGoal(problem_id=1801)

generator.change_goal(
    {
        get_fluent("communicated_soil_data", ["waypoint waypoint2"]),
        get_fluent("communicated_rock_data", ["waypoint waypoint3"]),
        get_fluent(
            "communicated_image_data", ["objective objective1", "mode high_res"]
        ),
    }
)
traces.append(generator.generate_trace())

generator.change_goal(
    {
        get_fluent("communicated_soil_data", ["waypoint waypoint2"]),
        get_fluent("communicated_rock_data", ["waypoint waypoint3"]),
        get_fluent(
            "communicated_image_data", ["objective objective1", "mode high_res"]
        ),
    }
)
traces.append(generator.generate_trace())

observations = traces.tokenize(PartialObservation, percent_missing=0.60)
model = extract.Extract(
    observations,
    extract.modes.ARMS,
    upper_bound=2,
    min_support=2,
    action_weight=110,
    info_weight=100,
    threshold=0.6,
    info3_default=30,
    plan_default=30,
)

print(model.details())

Output:

Model:
  Fluents: (at rover rover0 waypoint waypoint2), (have_soil_analysis rover rover0 waypoint waypoint2), (have_soil_analysis rover rover0 waypoint waypoint3), ...
  Actions:
    (communicate_image_data rover waypoint mode objective lander waypoint):
      precond:
        calibrated camera rover
        have_rock_analysis rover waypoint
        communicated_rock_data waypoint
        channel_free lander
        at_soil_sample waypoint
        at_rock_sample waypoint
      add:
        calibrated camera rover
        at rover waypoint
        have_image rover objective mode
        channel_free lander
        communicated_image_data objective mode
      delete:
        calibrated camera rover
    ...

  9class LearnedAction:
 10    def __init__(self, name: str, obj_params: List[str], **kwargs):
 11        self.name = name
 12        self.obj_params = obj_params
 13        if "cost" in kwargs:
 14            self.cost = kwargs["cost"]
 15
 16        self.precond = set() if "precond" not in kwargs else kwargs["precond"]
 17        self.add = set() if "add" not in kwargs else kwargs["add"]
 18        self.delete = set() if "delete" not in kwargs else kwargs["delete"]
 19
 20    def __eq__(self, other):
 21        return (
 22            isinstance(other, LearnedAction)
 23            and self.name == other.name
 24            and self.obj_params == other.obj_params
 25        )
 26
 27    def __hash__(self):
 28        # Order of obj_params is important!
 29        return hash(self.details())
 30
 31    def details(self):
 32        # obj_params can be either a list of strings or a list of PlanningObject depending on the token type and extraction method used to learn the action
 33        try:
 34            string = f"({self.name} {' '.join(self.obj_params)})"
 35        except TypeError:
 36            string = f"({self.name} {' '.join([o.details() for o in self.obj_params])})"
 37
 38        return string
 39
 40    def update_precond(self, fluents: Set[str]):
 41        """Adds preconditions to the action.
 42
 43        Args:
 44            fluents (set):
 45                The set of fluents to be added to the action's preconditions.
 46        """
 47        self.precond.update(fluents)
 48
 49    def update_add(self, fluents: Set[str]):
 50        """Adds add effects to the action.
 51
 52        Args:
 53            fluents (set):
 54                The set of fluents to be added to the action's add effects.
 55        """
 56        self.add.update(fluents)
 57
 58    def update_delete(self, fluents: Set[str]):
 59        """Adds delete effects to the action.
 60
 61        Args:
 62            fluents (set):
 63                The set of fluents to be added to the action's delete effects.
 64        """
 65        self.delete.update(fluents)
 66
 67    def clear(self):
 68        self.precond = set()
 69        self.add = set()
 70        self.delete = set()
 71
 72    def compare(self, orig_action: LearnedAction):
 73        """Compares the learned action to an original, ground truth action."""
 74        precond_diff = orig_action.precond.difference(self.precond)
 75        add_diff = orig_action.add.difference(self.add)
 76        delete_diff = orig_action.delete.difference(self.delete)
 77        return precond_diff, add_diff, delete_diff
 78
 79    def _serialize(self):
 80        return dict(
 81            name=self.name,
 82            obj_params=self.obj_params,
 83            cost=self.cost,
 84            precond=list(self.precond),
 85            add=list(self.add),
 86            delete=list(self.delete),
 87        )
 88
 89    @classmethod
 90    def _deserialize(cls, data):
 91        """Converts a json object to an Action."""
 92        precond = set(data["precond"])
 93        add = set(data["add"])
 94        delete = set(data["delete"])
 95        return cls(
 96            data["name"],
 97            data["obj_params"],
 98            cost=data["cost"],
 99            precond=precond,
100            add=add,
101            delete=delete,
102        )

class Model: 
 18class Model:
 19    """Action model.
 20
 21    An action model representing a planning domain. The characteristics of the
 22    model are dependent on the extraction technique used to obtain the model.
 23
 24    Attributes:
 25        fluents (set):
 26            The set of fluents in the domain.
 27        actions (set):
 28            The set of actions in the domain. Actions include their
 29            preconditions, add effects, and delete effects. The nature of the
 30            action attributes characterize the model.
 31    """
 32
 33    def __init__(
 34        self,
 35        fluents: Union[Set[LearnedFluent], Set[LearnedLiftedFluent]],
 36        actions: Union[Set[LearnedAction], Set[LearnedLiftedAction]],
 37    ):
 38        """Initializes a Model with a set of fluents and a set of actions.
 39
 40        Args:
 41            fluents (Union[Set[LearnedFluent], Set[str]]):
 42                The set of fluents in the model.
 43            actions (Set[LearnedAction]):
 44                The set of actions in the model.
 45        """
 46        self.fluents = fluents
 47        self.actions = actions
 48
 49    def __eq__(self, other):
 50        if not isinstance(other, Model):
 51            return False
 52        self_fluent_type, other_fluent_type = type(list(self.fluents)[0]), type(
 53            list(other.fluents)[0]
 54        )
 55        if self_fluent_type == other_fluent_type:
 56            return self.fluents == other.fluents and self.actions == other.actions
 57        if self_fluent_type == str:
 58            return set(map(lambda f: str(f), other.fluents)) == self.fluents
 59        if other_fluent_type == str:
 60            return set(map(lambda f: str(f), self.fluents)) == other.fluents
 61
 62    def details(self):
 63        # Set the indent width
 64        indent = " " * 2
 65        string = "Model:\n"
 66        # Map fluents to a comma separated string of the fluent names
 67        string += f"{indent}Fluents: {', '.join(map(str,self.fluents))}\n"
 68
 69        # Map the actions to a summary of their names, preconditions, add
 70        # effects and delete effects
 71        string += f"{indent}Actions:\n"
 72        for line in self._get_action_details().splitlines():
 73            string += f"{indent * 2}{line}\n"
 74        return string
 75
 76    def _get_action_details(self):
 77        # Set the indent width
 78        indent = " " * 2
 79        details = ""
 80        for action in self.actions:
 81            details += action.details() + ":\n"
 82            details += f"{indent}precond:\n"
 83            for f in action.precond:
 84                details += f"{indent * 2}{f}\n"
 85            details += f"{indent}add:\n"
 86            for f in action.add:
 87                details += f"{indent * 2}{f}\n"
 88            details += f"{indent}delete:\n"
 89            for f in action.delete:
 90                details += f"{indent * 2}{f}\n"
 91
 92        return details
 93
 94    def serialize(self, filepath: str = None):
 95        """Serializes the model into a json string.
 96
 97        Args:
 98            filepath (str):
 99                Optional; If supplied, the json string will be written to the
100                filepath.
101
102        Returns:
103            A string in json format representing the model.
104        """
105
106        serial = dumps(self._serialize(), cls=ComplexEncoder)
107        if filepath is not None:
108            with open(filepath, "w") as fp:
109                fp.write(serial)
110        return serial
111
112    def __to_tarski_formula(self, attribute: Set[str], lang: FirstOrderLanguage):
113        """Converts a set of strings (referencing an attribute of a LearnedAction, i.e. its preconditions)
114        to an Atom or CompoundFormula, in order to set up a tarski action.
115
116        Args:
117            attribute (Set[str]):
118                The attribute to be converted to an Atom or CompoundFormula.
119            lang (FirstOrderLanguage):
120                The relevant language.
121
122        Returns:
123            The attribute of the LearnedAction, converted to an Atom or CompoundFormula.
124        """
125        # return top if there are no constraints
126        if not attribute:
127            return top
128        # creates Atom
129        elif len(attribute) == 1:
130            return lang.get(list(attribute)[0].replace(" ", "_"))()  # type: ignore
131        # creates CompoundFormula
132        else:
133            return CompoundFormula(
134                Connective.And, [lang.get(a.replace(" ", "_"))() for a in attribute]  # type: ignore
135            )

138        self,

142        problem_filename: str = "",

146        if not domain_filename:
147            domain_filename = domain_name + ".pddl"
148        if not problem_filename:
149            problem_filename = problem_name + ".pddl"

155        elif isinstance(list(self.actions)[0], LearnedAction):

164    def to_pddl_lifted(
165        self,
166        domain_name: str,
167        problem_name: str,
168        domain_filename: str,
169        problem_filename: str,
170    ):
171        """Dumps a Model with typed lifted actions & fluents to PDDL files.
172
173        Args:
174            domain_name (str):
175                The name of the domain to be generated.
176            problem_name (str):
177                The name of the problem to be generated.
178            domain_filename (str):
179                The name of the domain file to be generated.
180            problem_filename (str):
181                The name of the problem file to be generated.
182        """
183        self.fluents: Set[LearnedLiftedFluent]
184        self.actions: Set[LearnedLiftedAction]
185
186        lang = tarski.language(domain_name)
187        problem = tarski.fstrips.create_fstrips_problem(
188            domain_name=domain_name, problem_name=problem_name, language=lang
189        )
190        sorts = set()
191
192        if self.fluents:
193            for f in self.fluents:
194                for sort in f.param_sorts:
195                    if sort not in sorts:
196                        lang.sort(sort)
197                        sorts.add(sort)
198
199                lang.predicate(f.name, *f.param_sorts)
200
201        if self.actions:
202            for a in self.actions:
203                vars = [lang.variable(f"x{i}", s) for i, s in enumerate(a.param_sorts)]
204
205                if len(a.precond) == 1:
206                    precond = lang.get(list(a.precond)[0].name)(*[vars[i] for i in list(a.precond)[0].param_act_inds])  # type: ignore
207                else:
208                    precond = CompoundFormula(
209                        Connective.And,
210                        [
211                            lang.get(f.name)(*[vars[i] for i in f.param_act_inds])  # type: ignore
212                            for f in a.precond
213                        ],
214                    )
215
216                adds = [lang.get(f.name)(*[vars[i] for i in f.param_act_inds]) for f in a.add]  # type: ignore
217                dels = [lang.get(f.name)(*[vars[i] for i in f.param_act_inds]) for f in a.delete]  # type: ignore
218                effects = [fs.AddEffect(e) for e in adds] + [fs.DelEffect(e) for e in dels]  # fmt: skip
219
220                problem.action(
221                    a.name,
222                    parameters=vars,
223                    precondition=precond,
224                    effects=effects,
225                )
226
227        problem.init = tarski.model.create(lang)  # type: ignore
228        problem.goal = land()  # type: ignore
229        writer = iofs.FstripsWriter(problem)
230        writer.write(domain_filename, problem_filename)

232    def to_pddl_grounded(
233        self,
234        domain_name: str,
235        problem_name: str,
236        domain_filename: str,
237        problem_filename: str,
238    ):
239        """Dumps a Model to two PDDL files. The conversion only uses 0-arity predicates, and no types, objects,
240        or parameters of any kind are used. Actions are represented as ground actions with no parameters.
241
242        Args:
243            domain_name (str):
244                The name of the domain to be generated.
245            problem_name (str):
246                The name of the problem to be generated.
247            domain_filename (str):
248                The name of the domain file to be generated.
249            problem_filename (str):
250                The name of the problem file to be generated.
251        """
252        lang = tarski.language(domain_name)
253        problem = tarski.fstrips.create_fstrips_problem(
254            domain_name=domain_name, problem_name=problem_name, language=lang
255        )
256        if self.fluents:
257            # create 0-arity predicates
258            for f in self.fluents:
259                # NOTE: want there to be no brackets in any fluents referenced as tarski adds these later.
260                # fluents (their string conversion) must be in the following format: (on object a object b)
261                test = str(f)
262                lang.predicate(str(f)[1:-1].replace(" ", "_"))
263        if self.actions:
264            for a in self.actions:
265                # fetch all the relevant 0-arity predicates and create formulas to set up the ground actions
266                preconds = self.__to_tarski_formula({a[1:-1] for a in a.precond}, lang)
267                adds = [lang.get(f"{e.replace(' ', '_')[1:-1]}")() for e in a.add]
268                dels = [lang.get(f"{e.replace(' ', '_')[1:-1]}")() for e in a.delete]
269                effects = [fs.AddEffect(e) for e in adds]
270                effects.extend([fs.DelEffect(e) for e in dels])
271                # set up action
272                problem.action(
273                    name=a.details()
274                    .replace("(", "")
275                    .replace(")", "")
276                    .replace(" ", "_"),
277                    parameters=[],
278                    precondition=preconds,
279                    effects=effects,
280                )
281        # create empty init and goal
282        problem.init = tarski.model.create(lang)
283        problem.goal = land()
284        # write to files
285        writer = iofs.FstripsWriter(problem)
286        writer.write(domain_filename, problem_filename)

class ARMS: 
 53class ARMS:
 54    """ARMS model extraction method.
 55
 56    Extracts a Model from state observations using the ARMS technique. Fluents
 57    are retrieved from the initial state. Actions are learned using the
 58    algorithm.
 59    """
 60
 61    class InvalidThreshold(Exception):
 62        def __init__(self, threshold):
 63            super().__init__(
 64                f"Invalid threshold value: {threshold}. Threshold must be a float between 0-1 (inclusive)."
 65            )
 66
 67    def __new__(
 68        cls,
 69        obs_tracelist: ObservedTraceList,
 70        debug: bool,
 71        upper_bound: int,
 72        min_support: int = 2,
 73        action_weight: int = 110,
 74        info_weight: int = 100,
 75        threshold: float = 0.6,
 76        info3_default: int = 30,
 77        plan_default: int = 30,
 78    ):
 79        """
 80        Arguments:
 81            obs_tracelist (ObservationLists):
 82                The observations to extract the model from.
 83            upper_bound (int):
 84                The upper bound for the maximum size of an action's preconditions and
 85                add/delete lists. Determines when an action schemata is fully learned.
 86            min_support (int):
 87                The minimum support count for an action pair to be considered frequent.
 88            action_weight (int):
 89                The constant weight W_A(a) to assign to each action constraint.
 90                Should be set higher than the weight of information constraints.
 91            info_weight (int):
 92                The constant weight W_I(r) to assign to each information constraint.
 93                Determined empirically, generally the highest in all constraints' weights.
 94            threshold (float):
 95                (0-1). The probability threshold θ to determine if an I3/plan constraint
 96                is weighted by its probability or set to a default value.
 97            info3_default (int):
 98                The default weight for I3 constraints with probability below the threshold.
 99            plan_default (int):
100                The default weight for plan constraints with probability below the threshold.
101        """
102        if obs_tracelist.type is not PartialObservation:
103            raise IncompatibleObservationToken(obs_tracelist.type, ARMS)
104
105        if not (threshold >= 0 and threshold <= 1):
106            raise ARMS.InvalidThreshold(threshold)
107
108        fluents = obs_tracelist.get_fluents()
109        # get fluents from initial state
110        # call algorithm to get actions
111        actions = ARMS._arms(
112            obs_tracelist,
113            upper_bound,
114            fluents,
115            min_support,
116            action_weight,
117            info_weight,
118            threshold,
119            info3_default,
120            plan_default,
121            debug,
122        )
123
124        # learned_fluents = set(map(lambda f: LearnedFluent(f.name, f.objects), fluents))
125        learned_fluents = set()
126        # format
127        for act in actions:
128            act.precond = {f"({p})" for p in act.precond}
129            act.add = {f"({p})" for p in act.add}
130            act.delete = {f"({p})" for p in act.delete}
131            learned_fluents.update(act.precond)
132            learned_fluents.update(act.add)
133            learned_fluents.update(act.delete)
134        return Model(learned_fluents, actions)
135
136    @staticmethod
137    def _arms(
138        obs_tracelist: ObservedTraceList,
139        upper_bound: int,
140        fluents: Set[Fluent],
141        min_support: int,
142        action_weight: int,
143        info_weight: int,
144        threshold: float,
145        info3_default: int,
146        plan_default: int,
147        debug: bool,
148    ) -> Set[LearnedAction]:
149        """The main driver for the ARMS algorithm."""
150        learned_actions = set()  # The set of learned action models Θ
151        # pointers to the earliest unlearned action for each observation list
152        early_actions = [0] * len(obs_tracelist)
153
154        debug1 = ARMS.debug_menu("Debug step 1?") if debug else False
155        connected_actions, action_map = ARMS.step1(obs_tracelist, debug1)
156        if debug1:
157            input("Press enter to continue...")
158
159        action_map_rev: Dict[LearnedAction, List[Action]] = defaultdict(list)
160        for obs_action, learned_action in action_map.items():
161            action_map_rev[learned_action].append(obs_action)
162
163        count = 1
164        while action_map_rev:
165            if debug:
166                print("Iteration", count)
167                count += 1
168
169            debug2 = ARMS.debug_menu("Debug step 2?") if debug else False
170            constraints, relation_map = ARMS.step2(
171                obs_tracelist,
172                connected_actions,
173                action_map,
174                fluents,
175                min_support,
176                debug2,
177            )
178            if debug2:
179                input("Press enter to continue...")
180
181            relation_map_rev: Dict[Relation, List[Fluent]] = defaultdict(list)
182            for fluent, relation in relation_map.items():
183                relation_map_rev[relation].append(fluent)
184
185            debug3 = ARMS.debug_menu("Debug step 3?") if debug else False
186            max_sat, decode = ARMS.step3(
187                constraints,
188                action_weight,
189                info_weight,
190                threshold,
191                info3_default,
192                plan_default,
193                debug3,
194            )
195            if debug3:
196                input("Press enter to continue...")
197
198            model = ARMS.step4(max_sat, decode)
199
200            debug5 = ARMS.debug_menu("Debug step 5?") if debug else False
201            # Mutates the LearnedAction (keys) of action_map_rev
202            ARMS.step5(
203                model,
204                list(action_map_rev.keys()),
205                debug5,
206            )
207
208            # Step 5 updates
209
210            # Progress observed states if early actions have been learned
211            setA = set()
212            for action in action_map_rev.keys():
213                for i, obs_trace in enumerate(obs_tracelist):
214                    obs_action: Action = obs_trace[early_actions[i]].action
215                    # if current action is the early action for obs_trace i,
216                    # update the next state with the effects and update the
217                    # early action pointer
218                    if obs_action in action_map and action == action_map[obs_action]:
219                        print()
220                        # Set add effects true
221                        for add in action.add:
222                            # get candidate fluents from add relation
223                            # get fluent by cross referencing obs_trace.action params
224                            candidates = relation_map_rev[add]
225                            for fluent in candidates:
226                                if set(fluent.objects).issubset(obs_action.obj_params):
227                                    obs_trace[early_actions[i] + 1].state[fluent] = True
228                                    early_actions[i] += 1
229                        # Set del effects false
230                        for delete in action.delete:
231                            candidates = relation_map_rev[delete]
232                            for fluent in candidates:
233                                if set(fluent.objects).issubset(obs_action.obj_params):
234                                    obs_trace[early_actions[i] + 1].state[
235                                        fluent
236                                    ] = False
237                                    early_actions[i] += 1
238
239                if debug:
240                    print()
241                    print(action.details())
242                    print("precond:", action.precond)
243                    print("add:", action.add)
244                    print("delete:", action.delete)
245
246                if (
247                    max([len(action.precond), len(action.add), len(action.delete)])
248                    >= upper_bound
249                ):
250                    if debug:
251                        print(
252                            f"Action schemata for {action.details()} has been fully learned."
253                        )
254                    setA.add(action)
255
256            # Update Λ by Λ − A
257            for action in setA:
258                action_keys = action_map_rev[action]
259                for obs_action in action_keys:
260                    del action_map[obs_action]
261                del action_map_rev[action]
262                del connected_actions[action]
263                action_keys = [
264                    a1 for a1 in connected_actions if action in connected_actions[a1]
265                ]
266                for a1 in action_keys:
267                    del connected_actions[a1][action]
268
269                # Update Θ by adding A
270                learned_actions.add(action)
271
272            if debug5:
273                input("Press enter to continue...")
274
275        return learned_actions
276
277    @staticmethod
278    def step1(
279        obs_tracelist: ObservedTraceList, debug: bool
280    ) -> Tuple[
281        Dict[LearnedAction, Dict[LearnedAction, Set[str]]],
282        Dict[Action, LearnedAction],
283    ]:
284        """(Step 1) Substitute instantiated objects in each action instance with the object type."""
285
286        learned_actions: Set[LearnedAction] = set()
287        action_map: Dict[Action, LearnedAction] = {}
288        for obs_action in obs_tracelist.get_actions():
289            # We don't support objects with multiple types right now, so no
290            # multiple type clauses need to be generated.
291
292            # Create LearnedActions for each action, replacing instantiated
293            # objects with the object type.
294            types = [obj.obj_type for obj in obs_action.obj_params]
295            learned_action = LearnedAction(obs_action.name, types)
296            learned_actions.add(learned_action)
297            action_map[obs_action] = learned_action
298
299        connected_actions: Dict[LearnedAction, Dict[LearnedAction, Set[str]]] = {}
300        for a1 in learned_actions:
301            connected_actions[a1] = {}
302            for a2 in learned_actions.difference({a1}):  # includes connecting with self
303                intersection = set(a1.obj_params).intersection(set(a2.obj_params))
304                if intersection:
305                    connected_actions[a1][a2] = intersection
306                    if debug:
307                        print(
308                            f"{a1.details()} is connected to {a2.details()} by {intersection}"
309                        )
310
311        return connected_actions, action_map
312
313    @staticmethod
314    def step2(
315        obs_tracelist: ObservedTraceList,
316        connected_actions: Dict[LearnedAction, Dict[LearnedAction, Set[str]]],
317        action_map: Dict[Action, LearnedAction],
318        fluents: Set[Fluent],
319        min_support: int,
320        debug: bool,
321    ) -> Tuple[ARMSConstraints, Dict[Fluent, Relation]]:
322        """(Step 2) Generate action constraints, information constraints, and plan constraints.
323
324        For the unexplained actions, build a set of information and action
325        constraints based on individual actions. Apply a frequent-set
326        mining algorithm to find the frequent sets of connected actions and
327        relations. Here connected means the actions and relations must share
328        some common parameters.
329        """
330
331        # Map fluents to relations
332        # relations are fluents but with instantiated objects replaced by the object type
333        relations: Dict[Fluent, Relation] = dict(
334            map(
335                lambda f: (
336                    f,
337                    Relation(
338                        f.name,
339                        [obj.obj_type for obj in f.objects],
340                    ),
341                ),
342                fluents,
343            )
344        )
345
346        debuga = ARMS.debug_menu("Debug action constraints?") if debug else False
347
348        action_constraints = ARMS.step2A(
349            connected_actions, set(relations.values()), debuga
350        )
351
352        debugi = ARMS.debug_menu("Debug info constraints?") if debug else False
353        info_constraints, info_support_counts = ARMS.step2I(
354            obs_tracelist, relations, action_map, debugi
355        )
356
357        debugp = ARMS.debug_menu("Debug plan constraints?") if debug else False
358        plan_constraints = ARMS.step2P(
359            obs_tracelist,
360            connected_actions,
361            action_map,
362            set(relations.values()),
363            min_support,
364            debugp,
365        )
366
367        return (
368            ARMSConstraints(
369                action_constraints,
370                info_constraints,
371                info_support_counts,
372                plan_constraints,
373            ),
374            relations,
375        )
376
377    @staticmethod
378    def step2A(
379        connected_actions: Dict[LearnedAction, Dict[LearnedAction, Set]],
380        relations: Set[Relation],
381        debug: bool,
382    ) -> List[Or[Var]]:
383        """Action constraints.
384
385        A1. The intersection of the precondition and add lists of all actions must be empty.
386
387        A2. In addition, if an action’s delete list includes a relation, this relation is
388        in the action’s precondition list. Thus, for every action, we require that
389        the delete list is a subset of the precondition list.
390        """
391
392        if debug:
393            print("\nBuilding action constraints...\n")
394
395        def implication(a: Var, b: Var):
396            return Or([a.negate(), b])
397
398        constraints: List[Or[Var]] = []
399        actions = set(connected_actions.keys())
400        for action in actions:
401            for relation in relations:
402                # A relation is relevant to an action if they share parameter types
403                if relation.matches(action):
404                    if debug:
405                        print(
406                            f'relation ({relation.var()}) is relevant to action "{action.details()}"\n'
407                            "A1:\n"
408                            f"  {relation.var()}∈ add ⇒ {relation.var()}∉ pre\n"
409                            f"  {relation.var()}∈ pre ⇒ {relation.var()}∉ add\n"
410                            "A2:\n"
411                            f"  {relation.var()}∈ del ⇒ {relation.var()}∈ pre\n"
412                        )
413
414                    # A1
415                    # relation in action.add => relation not in action.precond
416                    # relation in action.precond => relation not in action.add
417
418                    # (BREAK) marks unambiguous breakpoints for parsing later
419                    constraints.append(
420                        implication(
421                            Var(
422                                f"{relation.var()} (BREAK) in (BREAK) add (BREAK) {action.details()}"
423                            ),
424                            Var(
425                                f"{relation.var()} (BREAK) in (BREAK) pre (BREAK) {action.details()}"
426                            ).negate(),
427                        )
428                    )
429                    constraints.append(
430                        implication(
431                            Var(
432                                f"{relation.var()} (BREAK) in (BREAK) pre (BREAK) {action.details()}"
433                            ),
434                            Var(
435                                f"{relation.var()} (BREAK) in (BREAK) add (BREAK) {action.details()}"
436                            ).negate(),
437                        )
438                    )
439
440                    # A2
441                    # relation in action.del => relation in action.precond
442                    constraints.append(
443                        implication(
444                            Var(
445                                f"{relation.var()} (BREAK) in (BREAK) del (BREAK) {action.details()}"
446                            ),
447                            Var(
448                                f"{relation.var()} (BREAK) in (BREAK) pre (BREAK) {action.details()}"
449                            ),
450                        )
451                    )
452
453        return constraints
454
455    @staticmethod
456    def step2I(
457        obs_tracelist: ObservedTraceList,
458        relations: Dict[Fluent, Relation],
459        actions: Dict[Action, LearnedAction],
460        debug: bool,
461    ) -> Tuple[List[Or[Var]], Dict[Or[Var], int]]:
462        """Information constraints.
463
464        Suppose we observe a relation p to be true between two actions
465        \(a_n\) and \(a_{n+1}\) , and \(p, a_{i_1} , ... ,\) and \(a_{i_k}\) share
466        the same parameter types. We can represent this fact by the following clauses,
467        given that \(a_{i_1} , ... ,\) and \(a_{i_k}\) appear in that order.
468
469        I1. The relation \(p\) must be generated by an action \(a_{i_k} (0 \le i_k \le n)\),
470        that is, \(p\) is selected to be in the add-list of \(a_{i_k}\).
471        \(p∈ (add_{i_1} ∪ add_{i_2} ∪ \dots ∪ add_{i_k}) \), where ∪ means logical “or”.
472
473        I2. The last action \(a_{i_k}\) must not delete the relation p; that is,
474        \(p\) must not be selected to be in the delete list of \(a_{i_k}\): \(p \\not\in del_{i_k}\).
475
476        I3. We define the weight value of a relation-action pair \((p, a)\) as the
477        occurrence probability of this pair in all plan examples. If the probability
478        of a relation-action pair is higher than the probability threshold θ ,
479        then we set a corresponding relation constraint \(p ∈ \\text{PRECOND}_a\), which
480        receives a weight value equal to its prior probability.
481        """
482        if debug:
483            print("\nBuilding information constraints...")
484        constraints: List[Or[Var]] = []
485        support_counts: Dict[Or[Var], int] = defaultdict(int)
486        obs_trace: List[Observation]
487        for obs_trace_i, obs_trace in enumerate(obs_tracelist):
488            for i, obs in enumerate(obs_trace):
489                if obs.state is not None and i > 0:
490                    n = i - 1
491                    if debug:
492                        print(
493                            f"\nStep {i} of observation list {obs_trace_i} contains state information."
494                        )
495                    for fluent, val in obs.state.items():
496                        relation = relations[fluent]
497                        # Information constraints only apply to true relations
498                        if val:
499                            if debug:
500                                print(
501                                    f"  Fluent {fluent} is true.\n"
502                                    f"    ({relation.var()})∈ ("
503                                    f"{' ∪ '.join([f'add_{{ {actions[obs_trace[ik].action].details()} }}' for ik in range(0,n+1) if obs_trace[ik].action in actions] )}"  # type: ignore
504                                    ")"
505                                )
506                            # I1
507                            # relation in the add list of an action <= n (i-1)
508                            i1: List[Var] = []
509                            for obs_i in obs_trace[: i - 1]:
510                                if obs_i.action in actions and obs_i.action is not None:
511                                    ai = actions[obs_i.action]
512                                    if relation.matches(ai):
513                                        i1.append(
514                                            Var(
515                                                f"{relation.var()} (BREAK) in (BREAK) add (BREAK) {ai.details()}"
516                                            )
517                                        )
518
519                            # I2
520                            # relation not in del list of action n (i-1)
521                            i2 = None
522                            a_n = obs_trace[i - 1].action
523                            if a_n in actions and a_n is not None:
524                                i2 = Var(
525                                    f"{relation.var()} (BREAK) in (BREAK) del (BREAK) {actions[a_n].details()}"
526                                ).negate()
527
528                            if i1:
529                                constraints.append(Or(i1))
530                            if i2:
531                                constraints.append(Or([i2]))
532
533                            # I3
534                            # count occurences
535                            if (
536                                i < len(obs_trace) - 1
537                                and obs.action in actions
538                                and obs.action is not None  # for the linter
539                                and relation.matches(actions[obs.action])
540                            ):
541                                # corresponding constraint is related to the current action's precondition list
542                                support_counts[
543                                    Or(
544                                        [
545                                            Var(
546                                                f"{relation.var()} (BREAK) in (BREAK) pre (BREAK) {actions[obs.action].details()}"
547                                            )
548                                        ]
549                                    )
550                                ] += 1
551                            elif (
552                                a_n in actions
553                                and a_n is not None
554                                and relation.matches(actions[a_n])
555                            ):
556                                # corresponding constraint is related to the previous action's add list
557                                support_counts[
558                                    Or(
559                                        [
560                                            Var(
561                                                f"{relation.var()} (BREAK) in (BREAK) add (BREAK) {actions[a_n].details()}"
562                                            )
563                                        ]
564                                    )
565                                ] += 1
566
567        return constraints, support_counts
568
569    @staticmethod
570    def _apriori(
571        action_lists: List[List[LearnedAction]], minsup: int
572    ) -> Dict[Tuple[LearnedAction, LearnedAction], int]:
573        """An implementation of the Apriori algorithm to find frequent ordered pairs of actions."""
574        counts = Counter(
575            [action for action_list in action_lists for action in action_list]
576        )
577        # L1 = {actions that appear >minsup}
578        L1 = set(
579            frozenset([action])
580            for action in filter(lambda k: counts[k] >= minsup, counts.keys())
581        )  # large 1-itemsets
582
583        # Only going up to L2, so no loop or generalized algorithm needed
584        # apriori-gen step
585        C2 = set([i.union(j) for i in L1 for j in L1 if len(i.union(j)) == 2])
586        # Since L1 contains 1-itemsets where each item is frequent, C2 can
587        # only contain valid sets and pruning is not required
588
589        # Get all possible ordered action pairs
590        C2_ordered = set()
591        for pair in C2:
592            pair = list(pair)
593            C2_ordered.add((pair[0], pair[1]))
594            C2_ordered.add((pair[1], pair[0]))
595
596        # Count pair occurences and generate L2
597        frequent_pairs = {}
598        for ai, aj in C2_ordered:
599            count = 0
600            for action_list in action_lists:
601                a1_indecies = [i for i, e in enumerate(action_list) if e == ai]
602                if a1_indecies:
603                    for i in a1_indecies:
604                        if aj in action_list[i + 1 :]:
605                            count += 1
606            if count >= minsup:
607                frequent_pairs[(ai, aj)] = count
608
609        return frequent_pairs
610
611    @staticmethod
612    def step2P(
613        obs_tracelist: ObservedTraceList,
614        connected_actions: Dict[LearnedAction, Dict[LearnedAction, Set]],
615        action_map: Dict[Action, LearnedAction],
616        relations: Set[Relation],
617        min_support: int,
618        debug: bool,
619    ) -> Dict[Or[Var], int]:
620        """Plan constraints.
621
622        P1. Every precondition \(p\) of every action \(b\) must be in the add
623        list of a preceding action \(a\) and is not deleted by any actions between
624        \(a\) and \(b\).
625
626        P2. In addition, at least one relation \(r\) in the add list of an action
627        must be useful in achieving a precondition of a later action. That is, for
628        every action \(a\), an add list relation \(r\) must be in the precondition of a
629        later action \(b\), and there is no other action between \(a\) and \(b\)
630        that either adds or deletes \(r\).
631
632        "While constraints P1 and P2 provide the general guiding principle for
633        ensuring a plan’s correctness, in practice there are too many
634        instantiations of these constraints." (more information on the
635        rationelle in the paper) Thus, they are replaced with the following
636        constraints:
637
638        Let there be an action pair \(\langle a_i, a_j \\rangle, 0 \le i < j \le n-1\).
639
640        P3. One of the relevant relations \(p\) must be chosen to be in the
641        preconditions of both \(a_i\) and \(a_j\), but not in the delete list
642        of \(a_i\).
643
644        P4. The first action \(a_i\) adds a relevant relation that is in the
645        precondition list of the second action \(a_j\) in the pair.
646
647        P5. A relevant relation \(p\) that is deleted by the first action
648        \(a_i\) is added by \(a_j\). The second clause is designed for the event
649        when an action re-establishes a fact that is deleted by a previous action.
650
651        The above constraints can be combined into one constraint:
652        $$\exists p ((p \in (pre_i \cap pre_j) \land p \\not \in (del_i)) \lor (p \in (add_i \cap pre_j)) \lor (p \in (del_i \cap add_j)))$$
653        """
654        frequent_pairs = ARMS._apriori(
655            [
656                [
657                    action_map[obs.action]
658                    for obs in obs_trace
659                    if obs.action is not None and obs.action in action_map
660                ]
661                for obs_trace in obs_tracelist
662            ],
663            min_support,
664        )
665        if debug:
666            print("Frequent pairs:")
667            print(frequent_pairs)
668
669        # constraints: Dict[And[Or[Var]], int] = {}
670        constraints: Dict[Or[Var], int] = {}
671        for ai, aj in frequent_pairs.keys():
672            connectors = set()
673            # get list of relevant relations from connected_actions
674            if ai in connected_actions and aj in connected_actions[ai]:
675                connectors.update(connected_actions[ai][aj])
676            if aj in connected_actions and ai in connected_actions[aj]:
677                connectors.update(connected_actions[aj][ai])
678
679            # if the actions are not related they are not a valid pair for a plan constraint.
680            if not connectors:
681                continue
682
683            # for each relation, save constraint
684            relevant_relations = {p for p in relations if connectors.issubset(p.types)}
685            # relation_constraints: List[Or[And[Var]]] = []
686            relation_constraints: List[Var] = []
687            for relation in relevant_relations:
688                relation_constraints.append(
689                    Var(
690                        f"{relation.var()} (BREAK) relevant (BREAK) {ai.details()} (BREAK) {aj.details()}"
691                    )
692                )
693                if debug:
694                    print(
695                        f"{relation.var()} might explain action pair ({ai.details()}, {aj.details()})"
696                    )
697            constraints[Or(relation_constraints)] = frequent_pairs[(ai, aj)]
698
699        return constraints
700
701    @staticmethod
702    def step3(
703        constraints: ARMSConstraints,
704        action_weight: int,
705        info_weight: int,
706        threshold: float,
707        info3_default: int,
708        plan_default: int,
709        debug: bool,
710    ) -> Tuple[WCNF, Dict[int, Hashable]]:
711        """(Step 3) Construct the weighted MAX-SAT problem based on the constraints and weight information found in Step 2."""
712
713        action_weights = [action_weight] * len(constraints.action)
714        info_weights = [info_weight] * len(constraints.info)
715        info3_weights = ARMS._calculate_support_rates(
716            list(constraints.info3.values()), threshold, info3_default
717        )
718        plan_weights = ARMS._calculate_support_rates(
719            list(constraints.plan.values()), threshold, plan_default
720        )
721        all_weights = action_weights + info_weights + info3_weights + plan_weights
722
723        info3_constraints = list(constraints.info3.keys())
724        plan_constraints = list(constraints.plan.keys())
725        all_constraints = (
726            constraints.action + constraints.info + info3_constraints + plan_constraints
727        )
728
729        constraints_w_weights: Dict[Or[Var], int] = {}
730        for constraint, weight in zip(all_constraints, all_weights):
731            if constraint == nnffalse:
732                continue
733            if constraint not in constraints_w_weights:
734                constraints_w_weights[constraint] = weight
735            elif weight != constraints_w_weights[constraint]:
736                if debug:
737                    warn(
738                        f"The constraint {constraint} has conflicting weights ({weight} and {constraints_w_weights[constraint]}). Choosing the smaller weight."
739                    )
740                constraints_w_weights[constraint] = min(
741                    weight, constraints_w_weights[constraint]
742                )
743
744        problem: And[Or[Var]] = And(list(constraints_w_weights.keys()))
745        weights = list(constraints_w_weights.values())
746
747        wcnf, decode = to_wcnf(problem, weights)
748        return wcnf, decode
749
750    @staticmethod
751    def _calculate_support_rates(
752        support_counts: List[int], threshold: float, default: int
753    ) -> List[int]:
754        # NOTE:
755        # In the paper, Z_Σ_P (denominator of the support rate formula) is
756        # defined as the "total pairs" in the set of plans. However, in the
757        # examples it appears that they use the max support count as the
758        # denominator. My best interpretation is then to use the max support
759        # count as the denominator to calculate the support rate.
760
761        z_sigma_p = max(support_counts)
762
763        def get_support_rate(count):
764            probability = count / z_sigma_p
765            return probability * 100 if probability > threshold else default
766
767        return list(map(get_support_rate, support_counts))
768
769    @staticmethod
770    def step4(max_sat: WCNF, decode: Dict[int, Hashable]) -> Dict[Hashable, bool]:
771        """(Step 4) Solve the MAX-SAT problem built in Step 3."""
772        solver = RC2(max_sat)
773
774        encoded_model = solver.compute()
775
776        if not isinstance(encoded_model, list):
777            # should never be reached
778            raise InvalidMaxSATModel(encoded_model)
779
780        # decode the model (back to nnf vars)
781        model: Dict[Hashable, bool] = {
782            decode[abs(clause)]: clause > 0 for clause in encoded_model
783        }
784
785        return model
786
787    @staticmethod
788    def step5(
789        model: Dict[Hashable, bool],
790        actions: List[LearnedAction],
791        debug: bool,
792    ):
793        """(Step 5) Extract the learned action effects from the solved model."""
794        action_map = {a.details(): a for a in actions}
795        negative_constraints = defaultdict(set)
796        plan_constraints: List[Tuple[str, LearnedAction, LearnedAction]] = []
797
798        # NOTE: only taking the top n (optimal number varies, determine
799        # empirically) constraints usually results in more accurate action
800        # models, however this is not a part of the paper and therefore not
801        # implemented.
802        for constraint, val in model.items():
803            constraint = str(constraint).split(" (BREAK) ")
804            relation = constraint[0]
805            ctype = constraint[1]  # constraint type
806            if ctype == "in":
807                effect = constraint[2]
808                action = action_map[constraint[3]]
809                if debug:
810                    print(
811                        f"Learned constraint: {relation} in {effect}_{action.details()}"
812                    )
813                if val:
814                    action_update = {
815                        "pre": action.update_precond,
816                        "add": action.update_add,
817                        "del": action.update_delete,
818                    }[effect]
819                    action_update({relation})
820                else:
821                    action_effect = {
822                        "pre": action.precond,
823                        "add": action.add,
824                        "del": action.delete,
825                    }[effect]
826                    if relation in action_effect:
827                        if debug:
828                            warn(
829                                f"Removing {relation} from {effect} of {action.details()}"
830                            )
831                        action_effect.remove(relation)
832                    negative_constraints[(relation, action)].add(effect)
833
834            else:  # store plan constraint
835                ai = action_map[constraint[2]]
836                aj = action_map[constraint[3]]
837                plan_constraints.append((relation, ai, aj))
838                if debug:
839                    print(f"{relation} possibly explains action pair ({ai}, {aj})")
840
841        for p, ai, aj in plan_constraints:
842            if (
843                not (
844                    p in ai.precond.intersection(aj.precond) and p not in ai.delete
845                )  # P3
846                or not (p in ai.add.intersection(aj.precond))  # P4
847                or not (p in ai.delete.intersection(aj.add))  # P5
848            ):
849                # check if either P3 or P4 are partially fulfilled and can be satisfied
850                if p in ai.precond.union(aj.precond):
851                    if p in aj.precond:
852                        # if P3 isn't contradicted, add p to ai.precond
853                        if p not in ai.delete and not (
854                            (p, ai) in negative_constraints
855                            and "pre" in negative_constraints[(p, ai)]
856                        ):
857                            ai.update_precond({p})
858
859                        # if P4 isn't contradicted, add p to ai.add
860                        if not (
861                            (p, ai) in negative_constraints
862                            and "add" in negative_constraints[(p, ai)]
863                        ):
864                            ai.update_add({p})
865
866                    # p in ai.precond and P3 not contradicted, add p to aj.precond
867                    elif p not in ai.delete and not (
868                        (p, aj) in negative_constraints
869                        and "pre" in negative_constraints[(p, aj)]
870                    ):
871                        aj.update_precond({p})
872
873                # check if either P3 or P4 can be satisfied
874                elif not (
875                    (p, aj) in negative_constraints
876                    and "pre" in negative_constraints[(p, aj)]
877                ):
878                    # if P3 isn't contradicted, add p to both ai and aj preconds
879                    if p not in ai.delete and not (
880                        (p, ai) in negative_constraints
881                        and "pre" in negative_constraints[(p, ai)]
882                    ):
883                        ai.update_precond({p})
884                        aj.update_precond({p})
885
886                    # if P4 isn't contradicted, add p to ai.add and aj.precond
887                    if not (
888                        (p, ai) in negative_constraints
889                        and "add" in negative_constraints[(p, ai)]
890                    ):
891                        ai.update_add({p})
892                        aj.update_precond({p})
893
894                # check if P5 can be satisfied
895                # if P5 isn't contradicted, add p wherever it is missing
896                if not (
897                    (p, ai) in negative_constraints
898                    and "del" in negative_constraints[(p, ai)]
899                ) and not (
900                    (p, aj) in negative_constraints
901                    and "add" in negative_constraints[(p, aj)]
902                ):
903                    if p not in ai.delete:
904                        ai.update_delete({p})
905                    if p not in aj.add:
906                        aj.update_add({p})
907
908    @staticmethod
909    def debug_menu(prompt: str):
910        choice = input(prompt + " (y/n): ").lower()
911        while choice not in ["y", "n"]:
912            choice = input(prompt + " (y/n): ").lower()
913        return choice == "y"

ARMS model extraction method.

Extracts a Model from state observations using the ARMS technique. Fluents are retrieved from the initial state. Actions are learned using the algorithm.

ARMS( obs_tracelist: macq.observation.observed_tracelist.ObservedTraceList, debug: bool, upper_bound: int, min_support: int = 2, action_weight: int = 110, info_weight: int = 100, threshold: float = 0.6, info3_default: int = 30, plan_default: int = 30) 
 67    def __new__(
 68        cls,
 69        obs_tracelist: ObservedTraceList,
 70        debug: bool,
 71        upper_bound: int,
 72        min_support: int = 2,
 73        action_weight: int = 110,
 74        info_weight: int = 100,
 75        threshold: float = 0.6,
 76        info3_default: int = 30,
 77        plan_default: int = 30,
 78    ):
 79        """
 80        Arguments:
 81            obs_tracelist (ObservationLists):
 82                The observations to extract the model from.
 83            upper_bound (int):
 84                The upper bound for the maximum size of an action's preconditions and
 85                add/delete lists. Determines when an action schemata is fully learned.
 86            min_support (int):
 87                The minimum support count for an action pair to be considered frequent.
 88            action_weight (int):
 89                The constant weight W_A(a) to assign to each action constraint.
 90                Should be set higher than the weight of information constraints.
 91            info_weight (int):
 92                The constant weight W_I(r) to assign to each information constraint.
 93                Determined empirically, generally the highest in all constraints' weights.
 94            threshold (float):
 95                (0-1). The probability threshold θ to determine if an I3/plan constraint
 96                is weighted by its probability or set to a default value.
 97            info3_default (int):
 98                The default weight for I3 constraints with probability below the threshold.
 99            plan_default (int):
100                The default weight for plan constraints with probability below the threshold.
101        """
102        if obs_tracelist.type is not PartialObservation:
103            raise IncompatibleObservationToken(obs_tracelist.type, ARMS)
104
105        if not (threshold >= 0 and threshold <= 1):
106            raise ARMS.InvalidThreshold(threshold)
107
108        fluents = obs_tracelist.get_fluents()
109        # get fluents from initial state
110        # call algorithm to get actions
111        actions = ARMS._arms(
112            obs_tracelist,
113            upper_bound,
114            fluents,
115            min_support,
116            action_weight,
117            info_weight,
118            threshold,
119            info3_default,
120            plan_default,
121            debug,
122        )
123
124        # learned_fluents = set(map(lambda f: LearnedFluent(f.name, f.objects), fluents))
125        learned_fluents = set()
126        # format
127        for act in actions:
128            act.precond = {f"({p})" for p in act.precond}
129            act.add = {f"({p})" for p in act.add}
130            act.delete = {f"({p})" for p in act.delete}
131            learned_fluents.update(act.precond)
132            learned_fluents.update(act.add)
133            learned_fluents.update(act.delete)
134        return Model(learned_fluents, actions)

Determines when an action schemata is fully learned. min_support (int): The minimum support count for an action pair to be considered frequent. action_weight (int): The constant weight W_A(a) to assign to each action constraint. Should be set higher than the weight of information constraints. info_weight (int): The constant weight W_I(r) to assign to each information constraint. Determined empirically, generally the highest in all constraints' weights. threshold (float): (0-1). @staticmethod
def step1( obs_tracelist: macq.observation.observed_tracelist.ObservedTraceList, debug: bool) -> Tuple[Dict[LearnedAction, Dict[LearnedAction, Set[str]]], Dict[macq.trace.action.Action, LearnedAction]]: 
277    @staticmethod
278    def step1(
279        obs_tracelist: ObservedTraceList, debug: bool
280    ) -> Tuple[
281        Dict[LearnedAction, Dict[LearnedAction, Set[str]]],
282        Dict[Action, LearnedAction],
283    ]:
284        """(Step 1) Substitute instantiated objects in each action instance with the object type."""
285
286        learned_actions: Set[LearnedAction] = set()
287        action_map: Dict[Action, LearnedAction] = {}
288        for obs_action in obs_tracelist.get_actions():
289            # We don't support objects with multiple types right now, so no
290            # multiple type clauses need to be generated.
291
292            # Create LearnedActions for each action, replacing instantiated
293            # objects with the object type.
294            types = [obj.obj_type for obj in obs_action.obj_params]
295            learned_action = LearnedAction(obs_action.name, types)
296            learned_actions.add(learned_action)
297            action_map[obs_action] = learned_action
298
299        connected_actions: Dict[LearnedAction, Dict[LearnedAction, Set[str]]] = {}
300        for a1 in learned_actions:
301            connected_actions[a1] = {}
302            for a2 in learned_actions.difference({a1}):  # includes connecting with self
303                intersection = set(a1.obj_params).intersection(set(a2.obj_params))
304                if intersection:
305                    connected_actions[a1][a2] = intersection
306                    if debug:
307                        print(
308                            f"{a1.details()} is connected to {a2.details()} by {intersection}"
309                        )
310
311        return connected_actions, action_map
