(Step 2) Generate action constraints, information constraints, and plan constraints.

For the unexplained actions, build a set of information and action constraints based on individual actions. Apply a frequent-set mining algorithm to find the frequent sets of connected actions and relations. Here connected means the actions and relations must share some common parameters.

@staticmethod
def step2A( connected_actions: Dict[LearnedAction, Dict[LearnedAction, Set]], relations: Set[macq.extract.arms.Relation], debug: bool) -> List[nnf.Or[nnf.Var]]: 
377    @staticmethod
378    def step2A(
379        connected_actions: Dict[LearnedAction, Dict[LearnedAction, Set]],
380        relations: Set[Relation],
381        debug: bool,
382    ) -> List[Or[Var]]:
383        """Action constraints.
384
385        A1. The intersection of the precondition and add lists of all actions must be empty.
386
387        A2. In addition, if an action’s delete list includes a relation, this relation is
388        in the action’s precondition list. Thus, for every action, we require that
389        the delete list is a subset of the precondition list.
390        """
391
392        if debug:
393            print("\nBuilding action constraints...\n")
394
395        def implication(a: Var, b: Var):
396            return Or([a.negate(), b])
397
398        constraints: List[Or[Var]] = []
399        actions = set(connected_actions.keys())
400        for action in actions:
401            for relation in relations:
402                # A relation is relevant to an action if they share parameter types
403                if relation.matches(action):
404                    if debug:
405                        print(
406                            f'relation ({relation.var()}) is relevant to action "{action.details()}"\n'
407                            "A1:\n"
408                            f"  {relation.var()}∈ add ⇒ {relation.var()}∉ pre\n"
409                            f"  {relation.var()}∈ pre ⇒ {relation.var()}∉ add\n"
410                            "A2:\n"
411                            f"  {relation.var()}∈ del ⇒ {relation.var()}∈ pre\n"
412                        )
413
414                    # A1
415                    # relation in action.add => relation not in action.precond
416                    # relation in action.precond => relation not in action.add
417
418                    # (BREAK) marks unambiguous breakpoints for parsing later
419                    constraints.append(
420                        implication(
421                            Var(
422                                f"{relation.var()} (BREAK) in (BREAK) add (BREAK) {action.details()}"
423                            ),
424                            Var(
425                                f"{relation.var()} (BREAK) in (BREAK) pre (BREAK) {action.details()}"
426                            ).negate(),
427                        )
428                    )
429                    constraints.append(
430                        implication(
431                            Var(
432                                f"{relation.var()} (BREAK) in (BREAK) pre (BREAK) {action.details()}"
433                            ),
434                            Var(
435                                f"{relation.var()} (BREAK) in (BREAK) add (BREAK) {action.details()}"
436                            ).negate(),
437                        )
438                    )
439
440                    # A2
441                    # relation in action.del => relation in action.precond
442                    constraints.append(
443                        implication(
444                            Var(
445                                f"{relation.var()} (BREAK) in (BREAK) del (BREAK) {action.details()}"
446                            ),
447                            Var(
448                                f"{relation.var()} (BREAK) in (BREAK) pre (BREAK) {action.details()}"
449                            ),
450                        )
451                    )
452
453        return constraints

Action constraints.

A1. The intersection of the precondition and add lists of all actions must be empty.

A2. In addition, if an action’s delete list includes a relation, this relation is in the action’s precondition list. Thus, for every action, we require that the delete list is a subset of the precondition list.

@staticmethod
def step2I( obs_tracelist: macq.observation.observed_tracelist.ObservedTraceList, relations: Dict[macq.trace.fluent.Fluent, macq.extract.arms.Relation], actions: Dict[macq.trace.action.Action, LearnedAction], debug: bool) -> Tuple[List[nnf.Or[nnf.Var]], Dict[nnf.Or[nnf.Var], int]]: 
455    @staticmethod
456    def step2I(
457        obs_tracelist: ObservedTraceList,
458        relations: Dict[Fluent, Relation],
459        actions: Dict[Action, LearnedAction],
460        debug: bool,
461    ) -> Tuple[List[Or[Var]], Dict[Or[Var], int]]:
462        """Information constraints.
463
464        Suppose we observe a relation p to be true between two actions
465        \(a_n\) and \(a_{n+1}\) , and \(p, a_{i_1} , ... ,\) and \(a_{i_k}\) share
466        the same parameter types. We can represent this fact by the following clauses,
467        given that \(a_{i_1} , ... ,\) and \(a_{i_k}\) appear in that order.
468
469        I1. The relation \(p\) must be generated by an action \(a_{i_k} (0 \le i_k \le n)\),
470        that is, \(p\) is selected to be in the add-list of \(a_{i_k}\).
471        \(p∈ (add_{i_1} ∪ add_{i_2} ∪ \dots ∪ add_{i_k}) \), where ∪ means logical “or”.
472
473        I2. The last action \(a_{i_k}\) must not delete the relation p; that is,
474        \(p\) must not be selected to be in the delete list of \(a_{i_k}\): \(p \\not\in del_{i_k}\).
475
476        I3. We define the weight value of a relation-action pair \((p, a)\) as the
477        occurrence probability of this pair in all plan examples. If the probability
478        of a relation-action pair is higher than the probability threshold θ ,
479        then we set a corresponding relation constraint \(p ∈ \\text{PRECOND}_a\), which
480        receives a weight value equal to its prior probability.
481        """
482        if debug:
483            print("\nBuilding information constraints...")
484        constraints: List[Or[Var]] = []
485        support_counts: Dict[Or[Var], int] = defaultdict(int)
486        obs_trace: List[Observation]
487        for obs_trace_i, obs_trace in enumerate(obs_tracelist):
488            for i, obs in enumerate(obs_trace):
489                if obs.state is not None and i > 0:
490                    n = i - 1
491                    if debug:
492                        print(
493                            f"\nStep {i} of observation list {obs_trace_i} contains state information."
494                        )
495                    for fluent, val in obs.state.items():
496                        relation = relations[fluent]
497                        # Information constraints only apply to true relations
498                        if val:
499                            if debug:
500                                print(
501                                    f"  Fluent {fluent} is true.\n"
502                                    f"    ({relation.var()})∈ ("
503                                    f"{' ∪ '.join([f'add_{{ {actions[obs_trace[ik].action].details()} }}' for ik in range(0,n+1) if obs_trace[ik].action in actions] )}"  # type: ignore
504                                    ")"
505                                )
506                            # I1
507                            # relation in the add list of an action <= n (i-1)
508                            i1: List[Var] = []
509                            for obs_i in obs_trace[: i - 1]:
510                                if obs_i.action in actions and obs_i.action is not None:
511                                    ai = actions[obs_i.action]
512                                    if relation.matches(ai):
513                                        i1.append(
514                                            Var(
515                                                f"{relation.var()} (BREAK) in (BREAK) add (BREAK) {ai.details()}"
516                                            )
517                                        )
518
519                            # I2
520                            # relation not in del list of action n (i-1)
521                            i2 = None
522                            a_n = obs_trace[i - 1].action
523                            if a_n in actions and a_n is not None:
524                                i2 = Var(
525                                    f"{relation.var()} (BREAK) in (BREAK) del (BREAK) {actions[a_n].details()}"
526                                ).negate()
527
528                            if i1:
529                                constraints.append(Or(i1))
530                            if i2:
531                                constraints.append(Or([i2]))
532
533                            # I3
534                            # count occurences
535                            if (
536                                i < len(obs_trace) - 1
537                                and obs.action in actions
538                                and obs.action is not None  # for the linter
539                                and relation.matches(actions[obs.action])
540                            ):
541                                # corresponding constraint is related to the current action's precondition list
542                                support_counts[
543                                    Or(
544                                        [
545                                            Var(
546                                                f"{relation.var()} (BREAK) in (BREAK) pre (BREAK) {actions[obs.action].details()}"
547                                            )
548                                        ]
549                                    )
550                                ] += 1
551                            elif (
552                                a_n in actions
553                                and a_n is not None
554                                and relation.matches(actions[a_n])
555                            ):
556                                # corresponding constraint is related to the previous action's add list
557                                support_counts[
558                                    Or(
559                                        [
560                                            Var(
561                                                f"{relation.var()} (BREAK) in (BREAK) add (BREAK) {actions[a_n].details()}"
562                                            )
563                                        ]
564                                    )
565                                ] += 1
566
567        return constraints, support_counts

Information constraints.

Suppose we observe a relation p to be true between two actions (a_n) and (a_{n+1}) , and (p, a_{i_1} , ... ,) and (a_{i_k}) share the same parameter types. We can represent this fact by the following clauses, given that (a_{i_1} , ... ,) and (a_{i_k}) appear in that order.

I1. The relation (p) must be generated by an action (a_{i_k} (0 \le i_k \le n)), that is, (p) is selected to be in the add-list of (a_{i_k}). (p∈ (add_{i_1} ∪ add_{i_2} ∪ \dots ∪ add_{i_k}) ), where ∪ means logical “or”.

I2. The last action (a_{i_k}) must not delete the relation p; that is, (p) must not be selected to be in the delete list of (a_{i_k}): (p \not\in del_{i_k}).

I3. We define the weight value of a relation-action pair ((p, a)) as the occurrence probability of this pair in all plan examples. If the probability of a relation-action pair is higher than the probability threshold θ , then we set a corresponding relation constraint (p ∈ \text{PRECOND}_a), which receives a weight value equal to its prior probability.

@staticmethod
def step2P( obs_tracelist: macq.observation.observed_tracelist.ObservedTraceList, connected_actions: Dict[LearnedAction, Dict[LearnedAction, Set]], action_map: Dict[macq.trace.action.Action, LearnedAction], relations: Set[macq.extract.arms.Relation], min_support: int, debug: bool) -> Dict[nnf.Or[nnf.Var], int]: 
611    @staticmethod
612    def step2P(
613        obs_tracelist: ObservedTraceList,
614        connected_actions: Dict[LearnedAction, Dict[LearnedAction, Set]],
615        action_map: Dict[Action, LearnedAction],
616        relations: Set[Relation],
617        min_support: int,
618        debug: bool,
619    ) -> Dict[Or[Var], int]:
620        """Plan constraints.
621
622        P1. Every precondition \(p\) of every action \(b\) must be in the add
623        list of a preceding action \(a\) and is not deleted by any actions between
624        \(a\) and \(b\).
625
626        P2. In addition, at least one relation \(r\) in the add list of an action
627        must be useful in achieving a precondition of a later action. That is, for
628        every action \(a\), an add list relation \(r\) must be in the precondition of a
629        later action \(b\), and there is no other action between \(a\) and \(b\)
630        that either adds or deletes \(r\).
631
632        "While constraints P1 and P2 provide the general guiding principle for
633        ensuring a plan’s correctness, in practice there are too many
634        instantiations of these constraints." (more information on the
635        rationelle in the paper) Thus, they are replaced with the following
636        constraints:
637
638        Let there be an action pair \(\langle a_i, a_j \\rangle, 0 \le i < j \le n-1\).
639
640        P3. One of the relevant relations \(p\) must be chosen to be in the
641        preconditions of both \(a_i\) and \(a_j\), but not in the delete list
642        of \(a_i\).
643
644        P4. The first action \(a_i\) adds a relevant relation that is in the
645        precondition list of the second action \(a_j\) in the pair.
646
647        P5. A relevant relation \(p\) that is deleted by the first action
648        \(a_i\) is added by \(a_j\). The second clause is designed for the event
649        when an action re-establishes a fact that is deleted by a previous action.
650
651        The above constraints can be combined into one constraint:
652        $$\exists p ((p \in (pre_i \cap pre_j) \land p \\not \in (del_i)) \lor (p \in (add_i \cap pre_j)) \lor (p \in (del_i \cap add_j)))$$
653        """
654        frequent_pairs = ARMS._apriori(
655            [
656                [
657                    action_map[obs.action]
658                    for obs in obs_trace
659                    if obs.action is not None and obs.action in action_map
660                ]
661                for obs_trace in obs_tracelist
662            ],
663            min_support,
664        )
665        if debug:
666            print("Frequent pairs:")
667            print(frequent_pairs)
668
669        # constraints: Dict[And[Or[Var]], int] = {}
670        constraints: Dict[Or[Var], int] = {}
671        for ai, aj in frequent_pairs.keys():
672            connectors = set()
673            # get list of relevant relations from connected_actions
674            if ai in connected_actions and aj in connected_actions[ai]:
675                connectors.update(connected_actions[ai][aj])
676            if aj in connected_actions and ai in connected_actions[aj]:
677                connectors.update(connected_actions[aj][ai])
678
679            # if the actions are not related they are not a valid pair for a plan constraint.
680            if not connectors:
681                continue
682
683            # for each relation, save constraint
684            relevant_relations = {p for p in relations if connectors.issubset(p.types)}
685            # relation_constraints: List[Or[And[Var]]] = []
686            relation_constraints: List[Var] = []
687            for relation in relevant_relations:
688                relation_constraints.append(
689                    Var(
690                        f"{relation.var()} (BREAK) relevant (BREAK) {ai.details()} (BREAK) {aj.details()}"
691                    )
692                )
693                if debug:
694                    print(
695                        f"{relation.var()} might explain action pair ({ai.details()}, {aj.details()})"
696                    )
697            constraints[Or(relation_constraints)] = frequent_pairs[(ai, aj)]
698
699        return constraints

Plan constraints.

P1. Every precondition (p) of every action (b) must be in the add list of a preceding action (a) and is not deleted by any actions between (a) and (b).

P2. In addition, at least one relation (r) in the add list of an action must be useful in achieving a precondition of a later action. That is, for every action (a), an add list relation (r) must be in the precondition of a later action (b), and there is no other action between (a) and (b) that either adds or deletes (r).

"While constraints P1 and P2 provide the general guiding principle for ensuring a plan’s correctness, in practice there are too many instantiations of these constraints." (more information on the rationelle in the paper) Thus, they are replaced with the following constraints:

Let there be an action pair (\langle a_i, a_j \rangle, 0 \le i < j \le n-1).

P3. One of the relevant relations (p) must be chosen to be in the preconditions of both (a_i) and (a_j), but not in the delete list of (a_i).

P4. The first action (a_i) adds a relevant relation that is in the precondition list of the second action (a_j) in the pair.

P5. A relevant relation (p) that is deleted by the first action (a_i) is added by (a_j). The second clause is designed for the event when an action re-establishes a fact that is deleted by a previous action.

The above constraints can be combined into one constraint: $$\exists p ((p \in (pre_i \cap pre_j) \land p \not \in (del_i)) \lor (p \in (add_i \cap pre_j)) \lor (p \in (del_i \cap add_j)))$$

@staticmethod
def step3( constraints: macq.extract.arms.ARMSConstraints, action_weight: int, info_weight: int, threshold: float, info3_default: int, plan_default: int, debug: bool) -> Tuple[pysat.formula.WCNF, Dict[int, Hashable]]: 
701    @staticmethod
702    def step3(
703        constraints: ARMSConstraints,
704        action_weight: int,
705        info_weight: int,
706        threshold: float,
707        info3_default: int,
708        plan_default: int,
709        debug: bool,
710    ) -> Tuple[WCNF, Dict[int, Hashable]]:
711        """(Step 3) Construct the weighted MAX-SAT problem based on the constraints and weight information found in Step 2."""
712
713        action_weights = [action_weight] * len(constraints.action)
714        info_weights = [info_weight] * len(constraints.info)
715        info3_weights = ARMS._calculate_support_rates(
716            list(constraints.info3.values()), threshold, info3_default
717        )
718        plan_weights = ARMS._calculate_support_rates(
719            list(constraints.plan.values()), threshold, plan_default
720        )
721        all_weights = action_weights + info_weights + info3_weights + plan_weights
722
723        info3_constraints = list(constraints.info3.keys())
724        plan_constraints = list(constraints.plan.keys())
725        all_constraints = (
726            constraints.action + constraints.info + info3_constraints + plan_constraints
727        )
728
729        constraints_w_weights: Dict[Or[Var], int] = {}
730        for constraint, weight in zip(all_constraints, all_weights):
731            if constraint == nnffalse:
732                continue
733            if constraint not in constraints_w_weights:
734                constraints_w_weights[constraint] = weight
735            elif weight != constraints_w_weights[constraint]:
736                if debug:
737                    warn(
738                        f"The constraint {constraint} has conflicting weights ({weight} and {constraints_w_weights[constraint]}). Choosing the smaller weight."
739                    )
740                constraints_w_weights[constraint] = min(
741                    weight, constraints_w_weights[constraint]
742                )
743
744        problem: And[Or[Var]] = And(list(constraints_w_weights.keys()))
745        weights = list(constraints_w_weights.values())
746
747        wcnf, decode = to_wcnf(problem, weights)
748        return wcnf, decode

771        """(Step 4) Solve the MAX-SAT problem built in Step 3."""
772        solver = RC2(max_sat)

@staticmethod
def step5( model: Dict[Hashable, bool], actions: List[LearnedAction], debug: bool): 
787    @staticmethod
788    def step5(
789        model: Dict[Hashable, bool],
790        actions: List[LearnedAction],
791        debug: bool,
792    ):
793        """(Step 5) Extract the learned action effects from the solved model."""
794        action_map = {a.details(): a for a in actions}
795        negative_constraints = defaultdict(set)
796        plan_constraints: List[Tuple[str, LearnedAction, LearnedAction]] = []
797
798        # NOTE: only taking the top n (optimal number varies, determine
799        # empirically) constraints usually results in more accurate action
800        # models, however this is not a part of the paper and therefore not
801        # implemented.
802        for constraint, val in model.items():
803            constraint = str(constraint).split(" (BREAK) ")
804            relation = constraint[0]
805            ctype = constraint[1]  # constraint type
806            if ctype == "in":
807                effect = constraint[2]
808                action = action_map[constraint[3]]
809                if debug:
810                    print(
811                        f"Learned constraint: {relation} in {effect}_{action.details()}"
812                    )
813                if val:
814                    action_update = {
815                        "pre": action.update_precond,
816                        "add": action.update_add,
817                        "del": action.update_delete,
818                    }[effect]
819                    action_update({relation})
820                else:
821                    action_effect = {
822                        "pre": action.precond,
823                        "add": action.add,
824                        "del": action.delete,
825                    }[effect]
826                    if relation in action_effect:
827                        if debug:
828                            warn(
829                                f"Removing {relation} from {effect} of {action.details()}"
830                            )
831                        action_effect.remove(relation)
832                    negative_constraints[(relation, action)].add(effect)
833
834            else:  # store plan constraint
835                ai = action_map[constraint[2]]
836                aj = action_map[constraint[3]]
837                plan_constraints.append((relation, ai, aj))
838                if debug:
839                    print(f"{relation} possibly explains action pair ({ai}, {aj})")
840
841        for p, ai, aj in plan_constraints:
842            if (
843                not (
844                    p in ai.precond.intersection(aj.precond) and p not in ai.delete
845                )  # P3
846                or not (p in ai.add.intersection(aj.precond))  # P4
847                or not (p in ai.delete.intersection(aj.add))  # P5
848            ):
849                # check if either P3 or P4 are partially fulfilled and can be satisfied
850                if p in ai.precond.union(aj.precond):
851                    if p in aj.precond:
852                        # if P3 isn't contradicted, add p to ai.precond
853                        if p not in ai.delete and not (
854                            (p, ai) in negative_constraints
855                            and "pre" in negative_constraints[(p, ai)]
856                        ):
857                            ai.update_precond({p})
858
859                        # if P4 isn't contradicted, add p to ai.add
860                        if not (
861                            (p, ai) in negative_constraints
862                            and "add" in negative_constraints[(p, ai)]
863                        ):
864                            ai.update_add({p})
865
866                    # p in ai.precond and P3 not contradicted, add p to aj.precond
867                    elif p not in ai.delete and not (
868                        (p, aj) in negative_constraints
869                        and "pre" in negative_constraints[(p, aj)]
870                    ):
871                        aj.update_precond({p})
872
873                # check if either P3 or P4 can be satisfied
874                elif not (
875                    (p, aj) in negative_constraints
876                    and "pre" in negative_constraints[(p, aj)]
877                ):
878                    # if P3 isn't contradicted, add p to both ai and aj preconds
879                    if p not in ai.delete and not (
880                        (p, ai) in negative_constraints
881                        and "pre" in negative_constraints[(p, ai)]
882                    ):
883                        ai.update_precond({p})
884                        aj.update_precond({p})
885
886                    # if P4 isn't contradicted, add p to ai.add and aj.precond
887                    if not (
888                        (p, ai) in negative_constraints
889                        and "add" in negative_constraints[(p, ai)]
890                    ):
891                        ai.update_add({p})
892                        aj.update_precond({p})
893
894                # check if P5 can be satisfied
895                # if P5 isn't contradicted, add p wherever it is missing
896                if not (
897                    (p, ai) in negative_constraints
898                    and "del" in negative_constraints[(p, ai)]
899                ) and not (
900                    (p, aj) in negative_constraints
901                    and "add" in negative_constraints[(p, aj)]
902                ):
903                    if p not in ai.delete:
904                        ai.update_delete({p})
905                    if p not in aj.add:
906                        aj.update_add({p})

130    def _extract_aux_set_weights(
131        cnf_formula: And[Or[Var]], constraints: Dict, prob_disordered: float
132    ):
133        """Sets each clause in a CNF formula as a hard constraint, then sets any auxiliary variables to
134        the appropriate weight detailed in the "Constraint DC" section of the AMDN paper.
135        Used to help create disorder constraints.
136
137        Args:
138            cnf_formula (And[Or[Var]]):
139                The CNF formula to extract the clauses and auxiliary variables from.

151            # set each original constraint to be a hard clause
152            constraints[clause] = "HARD"

265    @staticmethod
266    def _build_disorder_constraints(obs_tracelist: ObservedTraceList):
267        """Builds disorder constraints. Corresponds to step 1 of the AMDN algorithm.
268
269        Args:
270            obs_tracelist (ObservationLists):
271                The tokens to be analyzed.
272
273        Returns:
274            The disorder constraints to be used in the algorithm.
275        """
276        disorder_constraints = {}
277
278        # iterate through all traces
279        for i in range(len(obs_tracelist.all_par_act_sets)):
280            # get the parallel action sets for this trace
281            par_act_sets = obs_tracelist.all_par_act_sets[i]
282            # iterate through all pairs of parallel action sets for this trace
283            # use -1 since we will be referencing the current parallel action set and the following one
284            for j in range(len(par_act_sets) - 1):
285                # for each action in psi_i+1
286                for act_y in par_act_sets[j + 1]:
287                    # for each action in psi_i
288                    # NOTE: we do not use an existential here, as the paper describes (for each act_y in psi_i + 1,
289                    # there exists an act_x in psi_i such that the condition holds.)
290                    # this is due to the fact that the weights must be set for each action pair.
291                    for act_x in par_act_sets[j]:
292                        if act_x != act_y:
293                            # calculate the probability of the actions being disordered (p)
294                            p = obs_tracelist.probabilities[ActionPair({act_x, act_y})]
295                            # each constraint only needs to hold for one proposition to be true
296                            constraint_1 = []
297                            constraint_2 = []
298                            for r in obs_tracelist.propositions:
299                                constraint_1.append(
300                                    Or(
301                                        [
302                                            And(
303                                                [
304                                                    pre(r, act_x),
305                                                    ~delete(r, act_x),
306                                                    delete(r, act_y),
307                                                ]
308                                            ),
309                                            And([add(r, act_x), pre(r, act_y)]),
310                                            And([add(r, act_x), delete(r, act_y)]),
311                                            And([delete(r, act_x), add(r, act_y)]),
312                                        ]
313                                    )
314                                )
315                                constraint_2.append(
316                                    Or(
317                                        [
318                                            And(
319                                                [
320                                                    pre(r, act_y),
321                                                    ~delete(r, act_y),
322                                                    delete(r, act_x),
323                                                ]
324                                            ),
325                                            And([add(r, act_y), pre(r, act_x)]),
326                                            And([add(r, act_y), delete(r, act_x)]),
327                                            And([delete(r, act_y), add(r, act_x)]),
328                                        ]
329                                    )
330                                )
331                            disjunct_all_constr_1 = Or(constraint_1).to_CNF()
332                            disjunct_all_constr_2 = Or(constraint_2).to_CNF()
333                            AMDN._extract_aux_set_weights(
334                                disjunct_all_constr_1, disorder_constraints, (1 - p)
335                            )
336                            AMDN._extract_aux_set_weights(
337                                disjunct_all_constr_2, disorder_constraints, p
338                            )
339        return disorder_constraints

341    @staticmethod
342    def _build_hard_parallel_constraints(obs_tracelist: ObservedTraceList):
343        """Builds hard parallel constraints.
344
345        Args:
346            obs_tracelist (ObservationLists):
347                The tokens to be analyzed.
348
349        Returns:
350            The hard parallel constraints to be used in the algorithm.
351        """
352        hard_constraints = {}
353        # create a list of all <a, r> tuples
354        for act in obs_tracelist.actions:
355            for r in obs_tracelist.propositions:
356                # for each action x proposition pair, enforce the two hard constraints with weight wmax
357                hard_constraints[implies(add(r, act), ~pre(r, act))] = WMAX
358                hard_constraints[implies(delete(r, act), pre(r, act))] = WMAX
359        return hard_constraints

361    @staticmethod
362    def _build_soft_parallel_constraints(obs_tracelist: ObservedTraceList):
363        """Builds soft parallel constraints.
364
365        Args:
366            obs_tracelist (ObservationLists):
367                The tokens to be analyzed.
368
369        Returns:
370            The soft parallel constraints to be used in the algorithm.
371        """
372        soft_constraints = {}
373
374        # NOTE: the paper does not take into account possible conflicts between the preconditions of actions
375        # and the add/delete effects of other actions (similar to the hard constraints, but with other actions
376        # in the parallel action set).
377
378        # iterate through all traces
379        for i in range(len(obs_tracelist.all_par_act_sets)):
380            par_act_sets = obs_tracelist.all_par_act_sets[i]
381            # iterate through all parallel action sets for this trace
382            for j in range(len(par_act_sets)):
383                # within each parallel action set, iterate through the same action set again to compare
384                # each action to every other action in the set; setting constraints assuming actions are not disordered
385                for act_x in par_act_sets[j]:
386                    for act_x_prime in par_act_sets[j] - {act_x}:
387                        p = obs_tracelist.probabilities[
388                            ActionPair({act_x, act_x_prime})
389                        ]
390                        # iterate through all propositions
391                        for r in obs_tracelist.propositions:
392                            soft_constraints[
393                                implies(add(r, act_x), ~delete(r, act_x_prime))
394                            ] = (1 - p) * WMAX
395
396        # iterate through all traces
397        for i in range(len(obs_tracelist.all_par_act_sets)):
398            par_act_sets = obs_tracelist.all_par_act_sets[i]
399            # then, iterate through all pairs of parallel action sets for each trace
400            for j in range(len(par_act_sets) - 1):
401                # for each pair, compare every action in act_y to every action in act_x_prime; setting constraints assuming actions are disordered
402                for act_y in par_act_sets[j + 1]:
403                    for act_x_prime in par_act_sets[j] - {act_y}:
404                        p = obs_tracelist.probabilities[
405                            ActionPair({act_y, act_x_prime})
406                        ]
407                        # iterate through all propositions and similarly set the constraint
408                        for r in obs_tracelist.propositions:
409                            soft_constraints[
410                                implies(add(r, act_y), ~delete(r, act_x_prime))
411                            ] = (p * WMAX)
412
413        return soft_constraints

415    @staticmethod
416    def _build_parallel_constraints(
417        obs_tracelist: ObservedTraceList, debug: bool, to_obs: Optional[List[str]]
418    ):
419        """Main driver for building parallel constraints. Corresponds to step 2 of the AMDN algorithm.
420
421        Args:
422            obs_tracelist (ObservationLists):
423                The tokens that were analyzed.
424            debug (bool):
425                Optional debugging mode.
426            to_obs (Optional[List[str]]):
427                If in the optional debugging mode, the list of fluents to observe.

430            The parallel constraints.
431        """
432        hard_constraints = AMDN._build_hard_parallel_constraints(obs_tracelist)
433        soft_constraints = AMDN._build_soft_parallel_constraints(obs_tracelist)
434        if debug:

441    @staticmethod
442    def _calculate_all_r_occ(obs_tracelist: ObservedTraceList):
443        """Calculates the total number of (true) propositions in the provided traces/tokens.
444
445        Args:
446            obs_tracelist (ObservationLists):
447                The tokens to be analyzed.
448
449        Returns:
450            The total number of (true) propositions in the provided traces/tokens.
451        """
452        # tracks occurrences of all propositions
453        all_occ = 0
454        for trace in obs_tracelist:
455            for step in trace:
456                all_occ += len([f for f in step.state if step.state[f]])
457        return all_occ

459    @staticmethod
460    def _set_up_occurrences_dict(obs_tracelist: ObservedTraceList):
461        """Helper function used when constructing noise constraints.
462        Sets up an "occurrence" dictionary used to track the occurrences of propositions
463        before or after actions.
464
465        Args:
466            obs_tracelist (ObservationLists):
467                The tokens to be analyzed.
468
469        Returns:
470            The blank "occurrences" dictionary.
471        """
472        # set up dict
473        occurrences = {}
474        for a in obs_tracelist.actions:
475            occurrences[a] = {}
476            for r in obs_tracelist.propositions:
477                occurrences[a][r] = 0
478        return occurrences

480    @staticmethod
481    def _noise_constraints_6(
482        obs_tracelist: ObservedTraceList, all_occ: int, occ_threshold: int
483    ):
484        """Noise constraints (6) in the AMDN paper.
485
486        Args:
487            obs_tracelist (ObservationLists):
488                The tokens that were analyzed.
489            all_occ (int):
490                The number of occurrences of all (true) propositions in the given observation list.
491            occ_threshold (int):
492                Threshold to be used for noise constraints.
493
494        Returns:
495            The noise constraints.
496        """
497        noise_constraints_6 = {}
498        occurrences = AMDN._set_up_occurrences_dict(obs_tracelist)
499
500        # iterate over ALL the plan traces, adding occurrences accordingly
501        for i in range(len(obs_tracelist)):
502            # iterate through each step in each trace, omitting the last step because the last action is None/we access the state in the next step
503            for j in range(len(obs_tracelist[i]) - 1):
504                true_prop = [
505                    f
506                    for f in obs_tracelist[i][j + 1].state
507                    if obs_tracelist[i][j + 1].state[f]
508                ]
509                for r in true_prop:
510                    # count the number of occurrences of each action and its following proposition
511                    occurrences[obs_tracelist[i][j].action][r] += 1
512
513        # iterate through actions
514        for a in occurrences:
515            # iterate through all propositions for this action
516            for r in occurrences[a]:
517                occ_r = occurrences[a][r]
518                # if the # of occurrences is higher than the user-provided threshold:
519                if occ_r > occ_threshold:
520                    # set constraint 6 with the calculated weight
521                    noise_constraints_6[AMDN._or_refactor(~delete(r, a))] = (
522                        occ_r / all_occ
523                    ) * WMAX
524        return noise_constraints_6
525
526    @staticmethod
527    def _noise_constraints_7(obs_tracelist: ObservedTraceList, all_occ: int):
528        """Noise constraints (7) in the AMDN paper.
529
530        Args:
531            obs_tracelist (ObservationLists):
532                The tokens that were analyzed.
533            all_occ (int):
534                The number of occurrences of all (true) propositions in the given observation list.
535
536        Returns:
537            The noise constraints.
538        """
539        noise_constraints_7 = {}
540        # set up dict
541        occurrences = {}
542        for r in obs_tracelist.propositions:
543            occurrences[r] = 0
544
545        for trace in obs_tracelist.all_states:
546            for state in trace:
547                true_prop = [r for r in state if state[r]]
548                for r in true_prop:
549                    occurrences[r] += 1
550
551        # iterate through all traces
552        for i in range(len(obs_tracelist.all_par_act_sets)):
553            # get the next trace/states
554            par_act_sets = obs_tracelist.all_par_act_sets[i]
555            states = obs_tracelist.all_states[i]
556            # iterate through all parallel action sets within the trace
557            for j in range(len(par_act_sets)):
558                # examine the states before and after each parallel action set; set constraints accordinglly
559                true_prop = [r for r in states[j + 1] if states[j + 1][r]]
560                for r in true_prop:
561                    if not states[j][r]:
562                        noise_constraints_7[
563                            Or([add(r, act) for act in par_act_sets[j]])
564                        ] = (occurrences[r] / all_occ) * WMAX
565        return noise_constraints_7

567    @staticmethod
568    def _noise_constraints_8(obs_tracelist, all_occ: int, occ_threshold: int):
569        """Noise constraints (8) in the AMDN paper.
570
571        Args:
572            obs_tracelist (ObservationLists):
573                The tokens that were analyzed.
574            all_occ (int):
575                The number of occurrences of all (true) propositions in the given observation list.
576            occ_threshold (int):
577                Threshold to be used for noise constraints.
578
579        Returns:
580            The noise constraints.
581        """
582        noise_constraints_8 = {}
583        occurrences = AMDN._set_up_occurrences_dict(obs_tracelist)
584
585        # iterate over ALL the plan traces, adding occurrences accordingly
586        for i in range(len(obs_tracelist)):
587            # iterate through each step in each trace
588            for j in range(len(obs_tracelist[i])):
589                # if the action is not None
590                if obs_tracelist[i][j].action:
591                    true_prop = [
592                        f
593                        for f in obs_tracelist[i][j].state
594                        if obs_tracelist[i][j].state[f]
595                    ]
596                    for r in true_prop:
597                        # count the number of occurrences of each action and its previous proposition
598                        occurrences[obs_tracelist[i][j].action][r] += 1
599
600        # iterate through actions
601        for a in occurrences:
602            # iterate through all propositions for this action
603            for r in occurrences[a]:
604                occ_r = occurrences[a][r]
605                # if the # of occurrences is higher than the user-provided threshold:
606                if occ_r > occ_threshold:
607                    # set constraint 8 with the calculated weight
608                    noise_constraints_8[AMDN._or_refactor(pre(r, a))] = (
609                        occ_r / all_occ
610                    ) * WMAX
611        return noise_constraints_8

613    @staticmethod
614    def _build_noise_constraints(
615        obs_tracelist: ObservedTraceList,
616        occ_threshold: int,
617        debug: bool,
618        to_obs: Optional[List[str]],
619    ):
620        """Driver for building all noise constraints. Corresponds to step 3 of the AMDN algorithm.
621
622        Args:
623            obs_tracelist (ObservationLists):
624                The tokens that were analyzed.
625            occ_threshold (int):
626                Threshold to be used for noise constraints.
627            debug (bool):
628                Optional debugging mode.
629            to_obs (Optional[List[str]]):
630                If in the optional debugging mode, the list of fluents to observe.
631        """
632        # calculate all occurrences for use in weights
633        all_occ = AMDN._calculate_all_r_occ(obs_tracelist)
634        nc_6 = AMDN._noise_constraints_6(obs_tracelist, all_occ, occ_threshold)
635        nc_7 = AMDN._noise_constraints_7(obs_tracelist, all_occ)
636        nc_8 = AMDN._noise_constraints_8(obs_tracelist, all_occ, occ_threshold)
637        if debug:
638            print("\nNoise constraints 6:")
639            AMDN._debug_simple_pprint(nc_6, to_obs)
640            print("\nNoise constraints 7:")
641            AMDN._debug_simple_pprint(nc_7, to_obs)
642            print("\nNoise constraints 8:")
643            AMDN._debug_simple_pprint(nc_8, to_obs)
644        return {**nc_6, **nc_7, **nc_8}

646    @staticmethod
647    def _set_all_constraints(
648        obs_tracelist: ObservedTraceList, occ_threshold: int, debug: bool
649    ):
650        """Main driver for generating all constraints in the AMDN algorithm.
651
652        Args:
653            obs_tracelist (ObservationLists):
654                The tokens that were analyzed.
655            occ_threshold (int):
656                Threshold to be used for noise constraints.
657            debug (bool):
658                Optional debugging mode.
659
660        Returns:
661            A dictionary that constains all of the constraints set and all of their weights.
662        """
663        to_obs = None

678    @staticmethod
679    def _solve_constraints(
680        obs_tracelist: ObservedTraceList, occ_threshold: int, debug: bool
681    ):
682        """Returns the WCNF and the decoder according to the constraints generated.
683        Corresponds to step 4 of the AMDN algorithm.
684
685        Args:
686            obs_tracelist (ObservationLists):
687                The tokens that were analyzed.
688            occ_threshold (int):
689                Threshold to be used for noise constraints.
690            debug (bool):
691                Optional debugging mode.
692
693        Returns:
694            The WCNF and corresponding decode dictionary.
695        """
696        constraints = AMDN._set_all_constraints(obs_tracelist, occ_threshold, debug)
697        # extract hard constraints
698        hard_constraints = []
699        for c, weight in constraints.items():
700            if weight == "HARD":
701                hard_constraints.append(c)
702        for c in hard_constraints:
703            del constraints[c]
704
705        wcnf, decode = to_wcnf(
706            soft_clauses=And(constraints.keys()),
707            hard_clauses=And(hard_constraints),
708            weights=list(constraints.values()),
709        )
710        return wcnf, decode

712    @staticmethod
713    def _split_raw_fluent(raw_f: Hashable, learned_actions: Dict[str, LearnedAction]):
714        """Helper function for `_extract_model` that updates takes raw fluents to update
715        a dictionary of `LearnedActions`.
716
717        Args:
718            raw_f (Hashable):
719                The raw fluent to parse.
720            learned_actions (Dict[str, LearnedAction]):
721                The dictionary of learned actions that will be used to create the model.
722        """
723        raw_f = str(raw_f)[1:-1]
724        pre_str = " is a precondition of "
725        add_str = " is added by "
726        del_str = " is deleted by "
727        if pre_str in raw_f:
728            f, act = raw_f.split(pre_str)
729            learned_actions[act].update_precond({f})
730        elif add_str in raw_f:
731            f, act = raw_f.split(add_str)
732            learned_actions[act].update_add({f})
733        else:
734            f, act = raw_f.split(del_str)
735            learned_actions[act].update_delete({f})

737    @staticmethod
738    def _extract_model(obs_tracelist: ObservedTraceList, model: Dict[Hashable, bool]):
739        """Converts a raw model generated from the pysat module into a macq `Model`.
740        Corresponds to step 5 of the AMDN algorithm.
741
742        Args:
743            obs_tracelist (ObservationLists):
744                The tokens that were analyzed.
745            model (Dict[Hashable, bool]):
746                The raw model to parse and analyze.
747
748        Returns:
749            The macq action `Model`.
750        """
751        # convert the result to a Model
752        fluents = obs_tracelist.propositions
753        # set up LearnedActions
754        learned_actions = {}
755        for a in obs_tracelist.actions:
756            # set up a base LearnedAction with the known information
757            learned_actions[a.details()] = extract.LearnedAction(
758                a.name, a.obj_params, cost=a.cost
759            )
760        # iterate through all fluents
761        for raw_f in model:
762            # update learned_actions (ignore auxiliary variables)
763            if not isinstance(raw_f, Aux) and model[raw_f]:
764                AMDN._split_raw_fluent(raw_f, learned_actions)
765        # format
766        actions = set(learned_actions.values())
767        for act in actions:
768            act.precond = {f"({p})" for p in act.precond}
769            act.add = {f"({p})" for p in act.add}
770            act.delete = {f"({p})" for p in act.delete}
771        return Model(fluents, actions)

189        cls,

192        viz: bool = False,
193        view: bool = False,
194        debug: Union[bool, Dict[str, bool], List[str]] = False,
195    ):
196        """Creates a new Model object.
197        Args:
198            observations (ObservationList):
199                The state observations to extract the model from.
200            statics (Dict[str, List[str]]):
201                A dictionary mapping an action name and its arguments to the
202                list of static preconditions of the action. A precondition should
203                be a tuple, where the first element is the predicate name and the
204                rest correspond to the arguments of the action (1-indexed).
205                E.g. static( next(C1, C2), put_on_card_in_homecell(C2, C1, _) )

210                Whether to view the FSM visualization.

213            IncompatibleObservationToken:
214                Raised if the observations are not identity observation.
215        """
216        if obs_tracelist.type is not ActionObservation:
217            raise IncompatibleObservationToken(obs_tracelist.type, LOCM)
218
219        if len(obs_tracelist) != 1:
220            warn("LOCM only supports a single trace, using first trace only")
221
222        if isinstance(debug, bool) and debug:
223            debug = defaultdict(lambda: True)
224        elif isinstance(debug, dict):
225            debug = defaultdict(lambda: False, debug)
226        elif isinstance(debug, list):
227            debug = defaultdict(lambda: False, {k: True for k in debug})
228        else:
229            debug = defaultdict(lambda: False)
230
231        obs_trace = obs_tracelist[0]
232        fluents, actions = None, None
233
234        sorts = LOCM._get_sorts(obs_trace, debug=debug["get_sorts"])
235
236        if debug["sorts"]:
237            sortid2objs = {v: [] for v in set(sorts.values())}
238            for k, v in sorts.items():
239                sortid2objs[v].append(k)
240            print("\nSorts:\n")
241            pprint(sortid2objs)
242            print("\n")

244        TS, ap_state_pointers, OS = LOCM._step1(obs_trace, sorts, debug["step1"])
245        HS = LOCM._step3(TS, ap_state_pointers, OS, sorts, debug["step3"])
246        bindings = LOCM._step4(HS, debug["step4"])
247        bindings = LOCM._step5(HS, bindings, debug["step5"])

260    @staticmethod
261    def _get_sorts(obs_trace: List[Observation], debug=False) -> Sorts:
262        sorts = []  # initialize list of sorts for this trace
263        # track actions seen in the trace, and the sort each actions params belong to
264        ap_sort_pointers: Dict[str, List[int]] = {}
265        # track objects seen in the trace, and the sort each belongs to
266        # obj_sort_pointers: Dict[str, int] = {}
267        sorted_objs = []
268
269        def get_obj_sort(obj: PlanningObject) -> int:
270            """Returns the sort index of the object"""
271            for i, sort in enumerate(sorts):
272                if obj in sort:
273                    return i
274            raise ValueError(f"Object {obj} not in any sort")
275
276        for obs in obs_trace:
277            action = obs.action
278            if action is None:
279                continue
280
281            if debug:
282                print("\n\naction:", action.name, action.obj_params)
283
284            if action.name not in ap_sort_pointers:  # new action
285                if debug:
286                    print("new action")
287
288                ap_sort_pointers[action.name] = []
289
290                # for each parameter of the action
291                for obj in action.obj_params:
292                    if obj.name not in sorted_objs:  # unsorted object
293                        # append a sort (set) containing the object
294                        sorts.append({obj})
295
296                        # record the object has been sorted and the index of the sort it belongs to
297                        obj_sort = len(sorts) - 1
298                        sorted_objs.append(obj.name)
299                        ap_sort_pointers[action.name].append(obj_sort)
300
301                        if debug:
302                            print("new object", obj.name)
303                            print("sorts:", sorts)
304
305                    else:  # object already sorted
306                        # look up the sort of the object
307                        obj_sort = get_obj_sort(obj)
308                        ap_sort_pointers[action.name].append(obj_sort)
309
310                        if debug:
311                            print("sorted object", obj.name)
312                            print("sorts:", sorts)
313
314                if debug:
315                    print("ap sorts:", ap_sort_pointers)
316
317            else:  # action seen before
318                if debug:
319                    print("seen action")
320
321                for ap_sort, obj in zip(
322                    ap_sort_pointers[action.name], action.obj_params
323                ):
324                    if debug:
325                        print("checking obj", obj.name)
326                        print("ap sort:", ap_sort)
327
328                    if obj.name not in sorted_objs:  # unsorted object
329                        if debug:
330                            print("unsorted object", obj.name)
331                            print("sorts:", sorts)
332
333                        # add the object to the sort of current action parameter
334                        sorts[ap_sort].add(obj)
335                        sorted_objs.append(obj.name)
336
337                    else:  # object already has a sort
338                        # retrieve the sort the object belongs to
339                        obj_sort = get_obj_sort(obj)
340
341                        if debug:
342                            print(f"retrieving sorted obj {obj.name}")
343                            print(f"obj_sort_idx: {obj_sort}")
344                            print(f"seq_sorts: {sorts}")
345
346                        # check if the object's sort matches the action paremeter's
347                        # if so, do nothing and move on to next step
348                        # otherwise, unite the two sorts
349                        if obj_sort == ap_sort:
350                            if debug:
351                                print("obj sort matches action")
352                        else:
353                            if debug:
354                                print(
355                                    f"obj sort {obj_sort} doesn't match action {ap_sort}"
356                                )
357                                print(f"seq_sorts: {sorts}")
358
359                            # unite the action parameter's sort and the object's sort
360                            sorts[obj_sort] = sorts[obj_sort].union(sorts[ap_sort])
361
362                            # drop the not unionized sort
363                            sorts.pop(ap_sort)
364
365                            old_obj_sort = obj_sort
366
367                            obj_sort = get_obj_sort(obj)
368
369                            if debug:
370                                print(
371                                    f"united seq_sorts[{ap_sort}] and seq_sorts[{obj_sort}]"
372                                )
373                                print(f"seq_sorts: {sorts}")
374                                print(f"ap_sort_pointers: {ap_sort_pointers}")
375                                print("updating pointers...")
376
377                            min_idx = min(ap_sort, obj_sort)
378
379                            # update all outdated records of which sort the affected objects belong to
380                            for action_name, ap_sorts in ap_sort_pointers.items():
381                                for p, sort in enumerate(ap_sorts):
382                                    if sort == ap_sort or sort == old_obj_sort:
383                                        ap_sort_pointers[action_name][p] = obj_sort
384                                    elif sort > min_idx:
385                                        ap_sort_pointers[action_name][p] -= 1
386
387                            if debug:
388                                print(f"ap_sort_pointers: {ap_sort_pointers}")
389
390        obj_sorts = {}
391        for i, sort in enumerate(sorts):
392            for obj in sort:
393                # NOTE: object sorts are 1-indexed so the zero-object can be sort 0
394                obj_sorts[obj.name] = i + 1
395
396        return obj_sorts

398    @staticmethod
399    def _pointer_to_set(states: List[Set], pointer, pointer2=None) -> Tuple[int, int]:
400        state1, state2 = None, None
401        for i, state_set in enumerate(states):
402            if pointer in state_set:
403                state1 = i
404            if pointer2 is None or pointer2 in state_set:
405                state2 = i
406            if state1 is not None and state2 is not None:
407                break
408
409        assert state1 is not None, f"Pointer ({pointer}) not in states: {states}"
410        assert state2 is not None, f"Pointer ({pointer2}) not in states: {states}"
411        return state1, state2

413    @staticmethod
414    def _step1(
415        obs_trace: List[Observation], sorts: Sorts, debug: bool = False
416    ) -> Tuple[TSType, APStatePointers, OSType]:
417        """Step 1: Create a state machine for each object sort
418        Implicitly includes Step 2 (zero analysis) by including the zero-object throughout
419        """
420
421        # create the zero-object for zero analysis (step 2)
422        zero_obj = LOCM.zero_obj
423
424        # collect action sequences for each object
425        obj_traces: Dict[PlanningObject, List[AP]] = defaultdict(list)
426        for obs in obs_trace:
427            action = obs.action
428            if action is not None:
429                # add the step for the zero-object
430                obj_traces[zero_obj].append(AP(action, pos=0, sort=0))
431                # for each combination of action name A and argument pos P
432                for j, obj in enumerate(action.obj_params):
433                    # create transition A.P
434                    ap = AP(action, pos=j + 1, sort=sorts[obj.name])
435                    obj_traces[obj].append(ap)
436
437        # initialize the state set OS and transition set TS
438        OS: OSType = defaultdict(list)
439        TS: TSType = defaultdict(dict)
440        # track pointers mapping A.P to its start and end states
441        ap_state_pointers = defaultdict(dict)
442        # iterate over each object and its action sequence
443        for obj, seq in obj_traces.items():
444            sort = sorts[obj.name] if obj != zero_obj else 0
445            TS[sort][obj] = seq  # add the sequence to the transition set
446            # max of the states already in OS[sort], plus 1
447            state_n = (
448                max([max(s) for s in OS[sort]] + [0]) + 1
449            )  # count current (new) state id
450            prev_states: StatePointers = None  # type: ignore
451            # iterate over each transition A.P in the sequence
452            for ap in seq:
453                # if the transition has not been seen before for the current sort
454                if ap not in ap_state_pointers[sort]:
455                    ap_state_pointers[sort][ap] = StatePointers(state_n, state_n + 1)
456
457                    # add the start and end states to the state set as unique states
458                    OS[sort].append({state_n})
459                    OS[sort].append({state_n + 1})
460
461                    state_n += 2
462
463                ap_states = ap_state_pointers[sort][ap]
464
465                if prev_states is not None:
466                    # get the state ids (indecies) of the state sets containing
467                    # start(A.P) and the end state of the previous transition
468                    start_state, prev_end_state = LOCM._pointer_to_set(
469                        OS[sort], ap_states.start, prev_states.end
470                    )
471
472                    # if not the same state set, merge the two
473                    if start_state != prev_end_state:
474                        OS[sort][start_state] = OS[sort][start_state].union(
475                            OS[sort][prev_end_state]
476                        )
477                        OS[sort].pop(prev_end_state)
478                    assert len(set.union(*OS[sort])) == sum([len(s) for s in OS[sort]])
479
480                prev_states = ap_states
481
482        # remove the zero-object sort if it only has one state
483        if len(OS[0]) == 1:
484            ap_state_pointers[0] = {}
485            OS[0] = []
486
487        return dict(TS), dict(ap_state_pointers), dict(OS)
488
489    @staticmethod
490    def _step3(
491        TS: TSType,
492        ap_state_pointers: APStatePointers,
493        OS: OSType,
494        sorts: Sorts,
495        debug: bool = False,
496    ) -> Hypotheses:
497        """Step 3: Induction of parameterised FSMs"""
498
499        zero_obj = LOCM.zero_obj
500
501        # indexed by B.k and C.l for 3.2 matching hypotheses against transitions
502        HS: Dict[HSIndex, Set[HSItem]] = defaultdict(set)
503
504        # 3.1: Form hypotheses from state machines
505        for G, sort_ts in TS.items():
506            # for each O ∈ O_u (not including the zero-object)
507            for obj, seq in sort_ts.items():
508                if obj == zero_obj:
509                    continue
510                # for each pair of transitions B.k and C.l consecutive for O
511                for B, C in zip(seq, seq[1:]):
512                    # skip if B or C only have one parameter, since there is no k' or l' to match on
513                    if len(B.action.obj_params) == 1 or len(C.action.obj_params) == 1:
514                        continue
515
516                    k = B.pos
517                    l = C.pos
518
519                    # check each pair B.k' and C.l'
520                    for i, Bk_ in enumerate(B.action.obj_params):
521                        k_ = i + 1
522                        if k_ == k:
523                            continue
524                        G_ = sorts[Bk_.name]
525                        for j, Cl_ in enumerate(C.action.obj_params):
526                            l_ = j + 1
527                            if l_ == l:
528                                continue
529
530                            # check that B.k' and C.l' are of the same sort
531                            if sorts[Cl_.name] == G_:
532                                # check that end(B.P) = start(C.P)
533                                # NOTE: just a sanity check, should never fail
534                                S, S2 = LOCM._pointer_to_set(
535                                    OS[G],
536                                    ap_state_pointers[G][B].end,
537                                    ap_state_pointers[G][C].start,
538                                )
539                                assert (
540                                    S == S2
541                                ), f"end(B.P) != start(C.P)\nB.P: {B}\nC.P: {C}"
542
543                                # save the hypothesis in the hypothesis set
544                                HS[HSIndex(B, k, C, l)].add(
545                                    HSItem(S, k_, l_, G, G_, supported=False)
546                                )
547
548        # 3.2: Test hypotheses against sequence
549        for G, sort_ts in TS.items():
550            # for each O ∈ O_u (not including the zero-object)
551            for obj, seq in sort_ts.items():
552                if obj == zero_obj:
553                    continue
554                # for each pair of transitions Ap.m and Aq.n consecutive for O
555                for Ap, Aq in zip(seq, seq[1:]):
556                    m = Ap.pos
557                    n = Aq.pos
558                    # Check if we have a hypothesis matching Ap=B, m=k, Aq=C, n=l
559                    BkCl = HSIndex(Ap, m, Aq, n)
560                    if BkCl in HS:
561                        # check each matching hypothesis
562                        for H in HS[BkCl].copy():
563                            # if Op,k' = Oq,l' then mark the hypothesis as supported
564                            if (
565                                Ap.action.obj_params[H.k_ - 1]
566                                == Aq.action.obj_params[H.l_ - 1]
567                            ):
568                                H.supported = True
569                            else:  # otherwise remove the hypothesis
570                                HS[BkCl].remove(H)
571
572        # Remove any unsupported hypotheses (but yet undisputed)
573        for hind, hs in HS.copy().items():
574            for h in hs.copy():
575                if not h.supported:
576                    hs.remove(h)
577            if len(hs) == 0:
578                del HS[hind]
579
580        # Converts HS {HSIndex: HSItem} to a mapping of hypothesis for states of a sort {sort: {state: Hypothesis}}
581        return Hypothesis.from_dict(HS)
582
583    @staticmethod
584    def _step4(HS: Hypotheses, debug: bool = False) -> Bindings:
585        """Step 4: Creation and merging of state parameters"""
586        # bindings = {sort: {state: [(hypothesis, state param)]}}
587        bindings: Bindings = defaultdict(dict)
588        for sort, hs_sort in HS.items():
589            for state, hs_sort_state in hs_sort.items():
590                # state_bindings = {hypothesis (h): state param (v)}
591                state_bindings: Dict[Hypothesis, int] = {}
592
593                # state_params = [set(v)]; params in the same set are the same
594                state_params: List[Set[int]] = []
595
596                # state_param_pointers = {v: P}; maps state param to the state_params set index
597                # i.e. map hypothesis state param v -> actual state param P
598                state_param_pointers: Dict[int, int] = {}
599
600                # for each hypothesis h,
601                hs_sort_state = list(hs_sort_state)
602                for v, h in enumerate(hs_sort_state):
603                    # add the <h, v> binding pair
604                    state_bindings[h] = v
605                    # add a param v as a unique state parameter
606                    state_params.append({v})
607                    state_param_pointers[v] = v
608
609                # for each (unordered) pair of hypotheses h1, h2
610                for i, h1 in enumerate(hs_sort_state):
611                    for h2 in hs_sort_state[i + 1 :]:
612                        # check if hypothesis parameters (v1 & v2) need to be unified
613                        if (
614                            (h1.B == h2.B and h1.k == h2.k and h1.k_ == h2.k_)
615                                    or   # See https://github.com/AI-Planning/macq/discussions/200
616                            (h1.C == h2.C and h1.l == h2.l and h1.l_ == h2.l_)  # fmt: skip
617                        ):
618                            v1 = state_bindings[h1]
619                            v2 = state_bindings[h2]
620
621                            # get the parameter sets P1, P2 that v1, v2 belong to
622                            P1, P2 = LOCM._pointer_to_set(state_params, v1, v2)
623
624                            if P1 != P2:
625                                # merge P1 and P2
626                                state_params[P1] = state_params[P1].union(
627                                    state_params[P2]
628                                )
629                                state_params.pop(P2)
630                                state_param_pointers[v2] = P1
631
632                                # fix state_param_pointers after v2
633                                for ind in range(v2 + 1, len(state_param_pointers)):
634                                    state_param_pointers[ind] -= 1
635
636                # add state bindings for the sort to the output bindings
637                # replacing hypothesis params with actual state params
638                bindings[sort][state] = [
639                    Binding(h, LOCM._pointer_to_set(state_params, v)[0])
640                    for h, v in state_bindings.items()
641                ]
642
643        return dict(bindings)
644
645    @staticmethod
646    def _step5(
647        HS: Hypotheses,
648        bindings: Bindings,
649        debug: bool = False,
650    ) -> Bindings:
651        """Step 5: Removing parameter flaws"""
652
653        # check each bindings[G][S] -> (h, P)
654        for sort, hs_sort in HS.items():
655            for state_id in hs_sort:
656                # track all the h.Bs that occur in bindings[G][S]
657                all_hB = set()
658                # track the set of h.B that set parameter P
659                sets_P = defaultdict(set)
660                for h, P in bindings[sort][state_id]:
661                    sets_P[P].add(h.B)
662                    all_hB.add(h.B)
663
664                # for each P, check if there is a transition h.B that never sets parameter P
665                # i.e. if sets_P[P] != all_hB
666                for P, setby in sets_P.items():
667                    if not setby == all_hB:  # P is a flawed parameter
668                        # remove all bindings referencing P
669                        for h, P_ in bindings[sort][state_id].copy():
670                            if P_ == P:
671                                bindings[sort][state_id].remove(Binding(h, P_))
672                        if len(bindings[sort][state_id]) == 0:
673                            del bindings[sort][state_id]
674
675                # do the same for checking h.C reading parameter P
676                # See https://github.com/AI-Planning/macq/discussions/200
677                all_hC = set()
678                reads_P = defaultdict(set)
679                if state_id in bindings[sort]:
680                    for h, P in bindings[sort][state_id]:
681                        reads_P[P].add(h.C)
682                        all_hC.add(h.C)
683                    for P, readby in reads_P.items():
684                        if not readby == all_hC:
685                            for h, P_ in bindings[sort][state_id].copy():
686                                if P_ == P:
687                                    bindings[sort][state_id].remove(Binding(h, P_))
688                            if len(bindings[sort][state_id]) == 0:
689                                del bindings[sort][state_id]
690
691        for k, v in bindings.copy().items():
692            if not v:
693                del bindings[k]
694
695        return bindings

699        import os
700
701        import networkx as nx
702
703        for sort in OS:
704            G = nx.DiGraph()
705            for n in range(len(OS[sort])):
706                lbl = f"state{n}"
707                if (
708                    state_params is not None
709                    and sort in state_params
710                    and n in state_params[sort]
711                ):
712                    lbl += str(
713                        [
714                            state_params[sort][n][v]
715                            for v in sorted(state_params[sort][n].keys())
716                        ]
717                    )
718                G.add_node(n, label=lbl, shape="oval")
719            for ap, apstate in ap_state_pointers[sort].items():
720                start_idx, end_idx = LOCM._pointer_to_set(
721                    OS[sort], apstate.start, apstate.end
722                )
723                # check if edge is already in graph
724                if G.has_edge(start_idx, end_idx):
725                    # append to the edge label
726                    G.edges[start_idx, end_idx][
727                        "label"
728                    ] += f"\n{ap.action.name}.{ap.pos}"
729                else:
730                    G.add_edge(start_idx, end_idx, label=f"{ap.action.name}.{ap.pos}")
731            # write to dot file
732            nx.drawing.nx_pydot.write_dot(G, f"LOCM-step7-sort{sort}.dot")
733            os.system(
734                f"dot -Tpng LOCM-step7-sort{sort}.dot -o LOCM-step7-sort{sort}.png"
735            )
736            os.system(f"rm LOCM-step7-sort{sort}.dot")
